Mother of infant received 2nd dose of Pfizer 9/21. Mother actively breast feeding infant. 24 hours after mother receiving 2nd vaccination, infant had significant bradycardia (drop in heart rate), desaturation ( low oxygen in the blood causing infant to turn blue). Infant was a previous 31 weeker adjusted to 36 weeks and discharge was pending at time mother received 2nd vaccination. After the initial episode, infant required a feeding tube due to feeding difficulties and lethargy. Infant was monitored in NICU with continued episodes of feeding difficulties associated with choking, inability to coordinate suck/swallow/breath, and bradycardic events. Head ultrasound was completed to show multiple cysts/hematomas (blood clots) present on the brain that were not present prior to vaccination. Infant was transferred to higher level of care for neurological evaluation. Due to absence of hematomas prior to vaccination and no evidence of head trauma, and  the known  vaccination side effects of potential blood clots; this shall be considered an adverse event.

a 70 y.o. female with past medical history of rheumatoid arthritis on chronic immunosuppressive therapy, hypertension hyperlipidemia, and diabetes who presents to the Emergency Department with chief complaint of as mentioned above.   The patient explains for about the last 10 days she has had progressive weakness.  Is getting progressively worse.  It is associated with some dizziness.  Early on she thought she had some blurred and double vision but this is resolved.  Patient says she has had a mild dry cough/tickle in her throat but denies any severe coughing or phlegm production.  She denies nausea or vomiting and says her appetite has been okay.  Due to her poor balance she has had to hold onto furniture to walk and has become increasingly weak.  She normally ambulates unassisted and is fully functional.  She denies fevers chills nausea vomiting or other constitutional symptoms.  She denies focal neurological deficits.  Her emergency evaluation revealed her to be hypoxic with a room air sat of 85%.  X-ray showed some vague infiltrate on the right side of her lung.  Subsequently her COVID-19 PCR has come back positive.  She did undergo an MRI of her brain showing no evidence of stroke.  He also appeared to be volume depleted with elevated BUN to creatinine ratio.  Due to her progressive symptoms she and COVID-19 pneumonia is developing she was admitted to hospital for further evaluation and treatment.  Of note the patient says she had her first COVID-19 vaccine approximately 5 days before her symptom onset.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient required hospitalization due to breakthrough infection. Patient received Pfizer vaccine (2nd dose in series) on 03/28/2021. Patient was hospitalized from 08/31/21 - 09/24/21.  Below is copied from patients discharge (death) summary:   Patient is a 73 y.o. female with PMH of RA/PMR and hypothyroidism who was initially admitted to the hospital on 8/31 for stroke like symptoms (left sided weakness, right facial droop and aphasia) for which she recieved TNK and had neuro ICU admission. MRI and stroke workup was unrevealing how patient remained enephalopathic with development of hypoxic respiratory failure requiring intubation from 9/5-9/14. Following extubation, patient was downgraded to hospitalist serevice for further management on 9/16. On 9/24, patient was admitted to MICU following cardiac arrest with asystole noted on telemetry. Patient recieved 6 rounds of CPR, epix3, bicarbx2, and calcium. She was intubated at that time and ROSC was achieved with post-resuscitation BP 100/50. Epi gtt was started and patient was admitted to MICU service. Immediately upon arrival to patient coded again at 4:21 AM with PEA arrest. She recieved Epix5, bicarbx3 with ROSC at 4:36. Upon achieving ROSC, patient again became pulseless with PEA arrest at which time an additional 3 rounds of CPR were performed however patient did not achieve ROSC and began to have copious blood return from ETT. Given patients anemia and active bleed, TNK was not administered as risks overweighed benefits. No further rounds of CPR performed. No  Subsequent spontaneous movements were present. There was no response to verbal or tactile stimuli. Pupils were dilated and fixed. No breath sounds were appreciated over either lung field. No carotid pulses or peripheral pulses were palpable. No heart sounds were auscultated over entire precordium. Patient pronounced dead at 5:16 AM.  Family was notified and condolensces were offered.

9/20 at 2:45pm at HCF.  Pt received a Pfizer #1 dose IM Lot Number FD 8448.  The vaccine was mixed at 2:15pm as per protocol.  At 3:05, Pt notified the student volunteer that she was having a itchiness in throat and around face. I arrived.  She explained that she has history of allergy and followed by an allergist. She takes Singular daily  and Benadryl as needed. She has an Epi-Pen and knows how to use.   She drove to herself to the COVID-19 vaccine clinic.  On assessment, no difficulty breathing, no stridor, able to talk with ease.  Escorted (walked) to another area of the clinic for privacy and observation.   Underneath the face mask, the client had a fine red rash in a butterfly shape over the cheeks and slight red in the forehead.  She stated that she was itchy on the tongue, no airway restriction, speech not affected. Based on assessment, I administered 25mg of Benadryl IM followed by 30 minute observation.   Benadryl 25mg administered in right deltoid..  Observed client for signs of increased symptoms. Rash became almost pink in color and faded toward the check line. No signs of distressed, syncope.  At 3:20  client walked outside of clinic area to parking lot to retrieve laptop.  Client spoke to on personal cell phone.   At 3:40 discussed dismissal options and giving an additional 25 mg of Benadryl.  Client elected to go home and contact provider.  Reinforced client to continue taking Benadryl every 6 hours.   Instructed client to see medical attention with primary care provider or urgent care if symptoms persist.  Client left at 3:42.
CUR_ILL: None reported.  Stated history of headache within last 10 days.

After both doses of vaccine, I had soreness and swelling in left vas at site of vasectomy.  Pain lasted about one week after each shot. Two weeks after second vaccination, I noticed I could no longer sleep on my left side without pressure in my chest. Pressure increased to pain in right side of chest. Pain would drop away throughout the day, but return at night about an hour and a half after going to bed. Pain continued to get worse over the course of about two months. Exercising with weights made the problem worse. Aerobic exercise did not effect the problem. I was an avid runner before getting vaccinated, but have since reduced my runs to about 3 times a week running about 2-3 miles at a time. At this time after about 7 months, I still have minor pain, but it is very minor. It can still occasionally be a problem lying on my right side. I continue to improve very slowly. I tried using aspirin at the peak of the pain and felt it might have helped a little bit. I have not seen a physician or taken any other medication.

He made an appointment with his opthamologist for 4/14/2021 to see if he could shed some light on the issues he is having. The office called and moved the appt to 4/22. At that appt, his pressures were 24 in his right eye (not the affected eye at that time) and 25 in his left eye. His left eye was extremely irritated so the doctor prescribed steroid drops to help calm down the irritation but could not make a determination for why the eye was irritated and the pressures were up, not to mention patient could hardly see the letters on the eye chart.He saw the opthamologist again on 5/19/2021 to see if the drops had helped. There was no improvement in vision or pressure. The pressures were 23 in R eye and 30 in left eye. The doctor recommended PT see a glaucoma specialist. They couldn't see him until 6/28/2021. At that appointment, his pressures were 22 in R and 36 in Left.Dr. preformed a visual field and recommended that drainage tubes (shunts) be inserted to drain fluid and relieve pressure. The surgery was scheduled for 7/27/2021. On 7/28/2021, PT returned to the doctor's office for a follow-up visit to check the surgery results. The pressure in his left eye was 29. Right wasn't checked. On 8/23/2021, PT had an appt with Dr. again and the left eye pressure was 25, which historically was not a good pressure for PT's left eye. However, the doctor seemed pleased that it had come down a few points in a month. The doctor still could not explain why the vision was still blurred and eye irritated, colors distorted and the flashing was still occurring. We decided to go to his opthamologist on 8/30/2021 and see if he could maybe correct the vision with glasses for right now. PT couldn't read the eye chart and during the exam, Dr. found a hole in his macula in his right eye and a warp in the macula in his left eye. His pressures were good at 16 and 15. Dr.. referred him to a retinal specialist. On 9/02/2021, PT saw retinal specialist, and the pressures checked 18 in the R eye and 23 in the L eye. He explained about a vitrectomy procedure which would repair the hole in the macula in the right eye. Needless to say, we are extremely discouraged at the inability to diagnose what has caused the blurred vision and other symptoms he is experiencing. He told retinal specialist he would have to think about the vitrectomy because his left eye is incapacitated now and if he has this procedure, he would be incapacitated in both eyes for a while. We have another appointment with the glaucoma specialist and the retinal specialist. We are hoping there is no permanent damage done but, at this time, we cannot say that there isn't. There has been no improvement since 3/2021. There is no exact date or time for the onset of the issues.
LAB_DATA: Visual Field administered by Dr. on 6/28/2021

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was fine the first day, but had pain in my right leg on the second day. It radiated down the entire leg, with the greatest pain in the hip. In bed, I would wake up when I turned over and put my weight on the right leg. Then, when I walked, I could not keep my right foot going straight, i.e., the foot would turn out at a 45 degree angle away from my left leg when I would step down. It was as if I had a "club foot." Dr. gave me some prescription strength Tylenol for the pain. I took those pills twice a day for two days and the pain was gone. However, it took at least two weeks before I could control my right foot when walking. (I have a dog and walk several miles per day.) FYI: I had a herniated disk in my back several years ago and pain radiating down my right leg. This pain was different -- not the sharp pain of a pinched nerve, but more of a muscular pain.  Also: During the several weeks my foot turned out when I walked, if I stood still and gently lifted my right leg and put my foot down in front of me, I could prevent it from turning. But the minute I walked, it just turned out. Very strange. I do not know if this was a result of the Covid vaccine, or just some strange muscular problem that basically cured itself.
LAB_DATA: No tests were given. Just the pain meds, which I took for just two days.

Around 11:00pm the night of the injection I started to not feel well and so went to bed. That night I was in and out of sleep and was very feverish. Around 3:00 my 12 month old daughter woke up to nurse. I felt so insanely horrible that I opted not to breastfeed, and rather to give her a bottle (which literally quite never happens). Until probably 6:30am, I remained awake, tossing and turning? writhing in pain. My head felt like it was absolutely going to explode and I was having the worst chills. I literally was crying I was in so much pain and was out of my mind with what I was enduring.  I was grasping on to my poor husband for warmth and making meek sounds of utter despair while tossing and turning, feeling as if God?s wrath was striking down on me.    I birthed two babies with no epidural and the pain in my head was comparable, if not more than that.   I got probably an hour and a half of sleep around 0600 and my husband noted that I was ?ablaze? and so put cold washcloths on my forehead and gave me a smoothie, ibuprofen, and water and let me rest . Around the afternoon time I had started to feel a little better, but started to get febrile and not feeling well come ~7:30, and so went to bed early. I felt better on Sunday.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving my second vaccine on Monday, (09/20/21) I had the usual symptoms of fever/chills/nausea/body aches for about 24 hours. Wednesday morning I again felt chest tightness but throughout the morning/afternoon I would notice times where I would feel like my heart was racing. I work at a health place on a- hospital campus. Our building  has Cardiac Rehab on our lower level. My co-worker convinced me to just go down and let them put the 3-lead monitor on me to make sure it was nothing serious. They did note some PAC?s and increased heart rate while just sitting at rest. My typical heart rate is low (50?s) when this was happening my heart rate would jump from 50?s to 100?s.   I have never experienced any type of heart issue or ever felt this type of thing happening before. I am a runner and athlete so I am relatively aware of odd occurrences in heart beat/rhythm along with my normal bodily functions. I still felt these weird bouts that my heart was racing throughout Wednesday evening. I have since not felt this happening again. I was advised to contact you. My employer  is a hospital system.

Patient was at his baseline health until after receiving his second SARS-CoV-2 vaccine (Pfizer) on Saturday, September 18th.  First developed symptoms of mild, diffuse headache, subjective fever and fatigue on Sunday, September 19th that progressed to some muscle aches into early last week.  However, on Wednesday, September 22nd, he developed substernal chest discomfort/pain associated with notably reduced functional capacity, SOB with activity, and worsening fatigue.  Pain was sudden described as sudden-onset while sitting in class, persisted for approximately 15 minutes and self-resolved.  Chest pain returned later that day and worsening by physical activity and coughing, being intermittently recurring until initial provider evaluation.  No associated rhinorrhea, congestion, conjunctivitis, recurrent fevers, rash, N/V, or changes in bowel/bladder habitus.   Evaluated by Peds on 9/24/21.  Vitals reassuring and physical examination unrevealing. Lab workup without evidence of WBC/CRP/ESR abnormalities and CMP unrevealing.  However, troponin elevated and EKG changes concerning initially for non-specific ST-T wave changes, but eventually referred to ED for further evaluation, where patient was noted to have significant ST-depression concerning for possible cardiac sequelae of underlying, unknown pathology. During admission, chest pain has improved and current being followed by Cardiology team.  Relevant labs: SARS-CoV-2 NP screen negative, troponin elevated (8,000+) but downtrending, normal pBNP, normal D-dimer, elevated LDH (250+), normal ferritin, negative respiratory pathogen panel, and only modest elevation of repeat CRP 0.55 mg/dL. CXR without acute abnormalities. Echocardiogram from 9/25/21 unrevealing .
OTHER_MEDS: Benzoyl peroxide-clindamycin topical gel (acne) Tretinoin cream topic QHS
CUR_ILL: None.  SARS-CoV-2 PCR positive (and symptomatic) early August 2021

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client reported that her legs felt "heavy" at 17:55 after completing her 15 minute observation period. The client denied any other s/s of anaphylaxis. The client stated that she spent several hours in the car on the way to the vaccination site. The client stated that her parents were in the vaccination room and that she was waiting for them. RN recommended the client stay in the observation area until her parents arrive. RN asked the client to report any changes in her symptoms or new onset of symptoms. The client voiced understanding of this. RN checked in with the client about 5 minutes later and the client stated the feeling was gone. At 18:30 the client reported itchiness and noticed redness on her thighs and neck. The client ambulated and sat down in the anti-gravity chair. RN responded. The client denied any shortness of breath or throat tightness. Vitals obtained at 18:30 were as follows: BP 137/87, HR 113, and O2 99%. The client stated she was concerned about a "rash on my legs." The client has no known allergies. She has no chronic conditions or medications. RN assessed the client's skin around the vaccination site, over her chest, neck, ankles, and face. RN did not note any urticaria or hives. The client showed RN a picture of her thighs which the client had taken while in the bathroom previously. RN viewed the picture and was unable to discern if there was a rash or redness present. The client's mother viewed the picture and stated that it looked abnormal for the client. The client was wearing jeans and RN was unable to view the client's thighs in person at the time. The client stated the itching was localized to her right knee and described it as intermittent. RN responded. Repeat vitals obtained at 18:35 were as follows: BP 137/97, HR 110, and O2 99%. RN discussed potential administration of Diphenhydramine. The client and her mother stated that she has not taken Diphenhydramine before. The client asked, "What will that help?" RN discussed the risks, benefits, and potential side effects of Diphenhydramine. RN noticed tears in the client's eyes. The client stated, "My throat kind of hurts, but it feels like I'm going to cry." The client denied any difficulty swallowing, shortness of breath, or constriction of her throat. The client requested to go to the restroom to look at her legs and requested RN accompany her. The client, RN, and the client's mother viewed the client's thighs with the client's permission in the restroom. RN noted stretch marks on the client's thigh which the client confirmed were normal for her. The client stated that her legs "look better." The client's mother stated the client's legs appeared normal. RN did not note any other redness or rash on the client's legs. Repeat vitals obtained at 18:45 PM were as follows: BP 133/94, HR 105, O2 99%. RN educated the client's mother in Spanish regarding s/s of anaphylaxis and when to seek EMS. The client's mother voiced understanding of this education. RN provided education to the client regarding s/s of anaphylaxis, when to seek EMS, and V-safe. The client's voiced understanding of this education. Vitals obtained at 18:54 were as follows: BP 127/71, HR 96, O2 98%. The client denied any current symptoms. The client was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation. The client stood up at 19:00 and walked unassisted with a steady gait out of the observation area.
Administration error mixed series mRNA vaccine Pfizer and Moderna

I layed down for about 10min. then sat back up  and started to experience severe left sided chest tightness and numbing of my entire left arm. It lasted about 2min. I then took two Asprin. Left side of chest still felt very heavy.  I was scared but decided to wait and call my doctor in the A. M.  My doctor's office suggest that I go to the ER to make sure I was not having a heart attack.  That morning I still had some numbing and tingling down the left arm with left sided chest tightness. I arrived to the ER where they did an EKG that should some abnormality. The ER nurse still made me wait in the waiting room for 2hrs. I finally got back to a room where I was seen by PA .  He ran some labs and came back and told me that my Lipase was at 706. Pa stated that I had acute pancreatitis. I was shocked as I am not a heavy drinker and maintain a pretty healthy lifestyle.  Doctor then recommended a CT scan to make sure nothing else was going on. CT showed normal pancreas. NO INFLAMMATION! Yet lab work stated inflammation of the Pancreas?!  A week later I had more blood work and my Lipase showed normal at 52?!

herpes zoster; postherpetic neuralgia; Ramsey Hunt Syndrome; trigeminal neuralgia; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation which referred to a patient (pt) of unknown gender and age. Information regarding concomitant medications, concurrent conditions or medical history was not provided. On an unknown date, the pt was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) (exact dose, dose number, route of administration, anatomical site of vaccination, lot number and expiration date were not provided). Afterwards, on an unknown date (reported as after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine), the pt suffered herpes zoster, postherpetic neuralgia, Ramsey Hunt Syndrome (herpes zoster oticus) and trigeminal neuralgia. As a result of those symptoms, the pt was seen and treated by medical providers and was still under their care. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the pt's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of pt's condition. In addition, the pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, the pt had suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. Finally, as direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was considered as not recovered. The causal relationship between the events and zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was assessed as related.  Herpes zoster, postherpetic neuralgia, trigeminal neuralgia, and herpes zoster oticus were considered as disabling events by the reporter.   Upon internal review, the event of herpes zoster oticus was determined to be medically significant.

SUSPECTED IMMUNOLOGICAL VACCINE FAILURE; INTENTIONAL PRODUCT MISUSE; OFF LABEL USE; This spontaneous report was received from literature. This report concerned a 9 decade old female of unspecified race and ethnic origin. The objective of this study was to describe Immunogenicity of Pfizer mRNA COVID-19 vaccination followed by J&J adenovirus COVID-19 vaccination in two CLL patients. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's concurrent conditions included: mild hypogammaglobulinemia, and chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), and other pre-existing medical conditions included no history of recurring infections or need for IgG supplementation. The patient was previously treated with obinutuzumab. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of administration not reported, batch number: unknown) dose not reported, 1 total, start therapy date were not reported for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported and has been requested. Concomitant medications included BNT 162 for prophylactic vaccination, and ibrutinib. The patient self-referred and received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s 81 days after completion of the BNT162 vaccine series (intentional product misuse and off label use). After 27 days following third vaccine additional samples were taken. It was reported that patient did not had pre-vaccination B-cell responses as measured by RBD-specific antibodies or MBC (Memory B-Cells) and did not had virus-specific CD8+ response at baseline. The patient had spike peptide-reactive CD4+ T-cells at baseline these cells were unresponsive and did not expand following vaccination. In contrast, CD8+ responses were observed after mRNA vaccination in the patient. Approximately four weeks after initial vaccination the patient had detectable RBD-specific SARS-CoV-2 antibodies or MBCs. The had measurable vaccine-induced CD8+ T-cell responses following mRNA vaccination, although CD4+ responses did not appear to increase above the baseline. The patient did not seroconvert or had detectable virus specific MBCs after their primary mRNA vaccination series however had a spike-specific CD8+ T-cell response that further boosted after a 3rd dose and a virus-specific CD4+ response that didn't change following original vaccine series or 3rd dose of J&J. The patient had undergone previous treatment (6 years ago) with obinutuzumab an anti-CD20 mAb and is currently on active treatment with Ibrutinib, since 2017. Both had baseline B-cell frequencies outside of the normal range. The patient had a low percentage of naive B-cells (11.37) and MBCs (0.45). Although the patient had mild hypogammaglobulinemia, the patient did not had history of recurring infection or need for IgG supplementation. The Levels of baseline CD4+ and CD8+ T cells (absolute values) were also normal, prior to vaccination (data not presented). The patient had very low percentage of naive B cells which could explains the initial poor response to vaccination. The patient had an increase in virus specific CD8+ T-cells. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The outcome of the suspected immunological vaccine failure, intentional product misuse and off label use was not reported. The author emphasized that 3rd vaccination against COVID-19 with the heterotypic vaccine Ad26COV2.s results in an immune response that was not observed following the recommended 2-dose mRNA vaccination series. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition). This report is associated with product quality complaint. This case, from the same reporter is linked to 20210944630. September 27, 2021  New nervous system reaction:  Over 20 years ago, I was diagnosed with RSD (Reflex Sympathetic Dystrophy) in my left knee.  I spent over 2 years rehabbing and have had no signs of this nervous system disease until Tuesday, September 21, 2021, about 1:15 pm.  While I was sitting at my desk working, sharp stabbing nerve pains in my left knee began to happen.  These pains were milder than my original episode over 20 years ago and only lasted until Sunday, September 26, 2021, 10:30 am.  This episode, happened quickly, like flipping a light switch on and ended quickly like, turning off a light.  At this time, Monday, September 27, 2021, there is no sign of this episode.  During those few days, of this episode, I reverted to treatments that I had done to help the RSD.  I was even able to work out normally this morning.   I have no idea if it has gone dormant again or if it will return any time soon, but I did feel it was necessary to add to my previous report (VAERS ID: 1675629 / E-Report Number:  636305).  Both of these incidents have been reported to my Primary Doctor  with no response.  I am definitely disappointed in the no response and terrified of another injection.  Thank you again for your time and I hope this information can be helpful for the future.
LAB_DATA: None, my primary doctor has not responded to any information that I have provided to him.

Patient presented to clinic at approximately 0615 the morning of 17 September 2021 complaining of diplopia in both eyes. Denied any headache, vertigo, nausea, vomiting, or pain associated with diplopia. Physical exam findings were unremarkable and patient was observed for approximately one hour before being released with return precautions and artificial tears for comfort. Patient returned to clinic approximately 4 hours later complaining of increased frequency of diplopia without any associated systems. Provider boarded patient on facilities Patient Care Unit for observation. Patient had no further complaints until the afternoon of 19 September where he began to complain that his diplopia was now constant with associated headache and vertigo. Patient transported to local hospital and was admitted for observation. Subsequent MRI on 20 September was negative for any abnormalities but patient began to lose Ocular Motor function later that day. Spinal tap on 23 September showed elevated protein levels in CSF and a subsequent diagnosis of Miller Fisher Syndrome was given. He was started on IgG therapy and currently remains at the inpatient unit with an anticipated discharge date of 28 September.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Big red rashes all over body.

I was very ill after the Moderna vaccine shot #1 (and #2- appears I must make a separate report for that?); I could not get out of bed for two days.   I felt light headed, sick, headache, body aches, was exhausted.

Leaving the store I thought my vision was a little hazy but also I was really tired so didn't think too much of it. When my husband came home from work for lunch later that day, I asked him if his vision was hazy or blurry after his second dose. He said no; so again I just brushed it off and forgot about it. Then that evening around 5:30 pm, I was feeling a little headache pulse behind my left ear and I was feeling tired. I asked my husband to take a picture of me because I wanted to see how tired I looked. It was then that I noticed my eyes were asymmetrical; one looked different with a droopy eye lid (kind of like a lazy-eye look). My vision still felt a little off so I went inside to start cooking. 20 minutes later I felt like my vision was normal and eventually went to sleep. The next day I woke up and felt like symptoms were all gone, until I remembered my right eye situation. I looked in the mirror and the right eye was still asymmetrical (droopy lid). It feels like the right eye is having to work harder. It is hard to explain but the right eye does not feel normal to me. I made an appt with an eye doctor that day and my vision checked out ok but she did diagnose ptosis of the right eyelid. Although I do see some improvement of the droopiness of the lid, it has not returned to its normal pre-shot state and the feeling I described is still there.
OTHER_MEDS: Prenatal Vitamin Prenatal DHA D3 Folate Coq10 Aspirin

Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine EUA: COVID-19 case resulting in Hospitalization / Death. Patient received Pfizer Vaccines on 3/12/2021 and 4/9/2021. Patient presented to emergency department on 8/26/21 with shortness of breath, cough, fatigue, and diarrhea, all starting 11 days prior to admission.  She was diagnosed with covid on 8/25.  She was admitted with acute respiratory failure with hypoxia due to covid 19 pneumonia.She was initially placed on airvo.  Inflammatory markers were elevated.  Her procalcitonin was elevated and she received and completed a course of Rocephin. She completed a 10-day course of Decadron and was changed to solumedrol.  She completed a course of remdesivir and baricitinib. She was subsequently started on cefepime with dense consolidation on her Xray. She was on Lovenox that was decreased to DVT prophylaxis dose.  Her echo showed normal LVEF of 55-60% with Grade II diastolic dysfunction. Her oxygen requirements increased, and she was intubated on 9/16. She was switched from solumedrol to a prednisone taper. Her Lovenox dose was changed to bariatric dose. She was continued on insulin.  Her Lovenox was switched to heparin.  She had worsening pulmonary fibrosis and developed hypoxia refractory to ventilatory support (saturations in the 60% range).  She was not deemed a candidate for CRRT.  ICU team met with family and her code status was changed to DNR/AND.  Patient's ventilation was deescalated. Patient expired at 1444 on 9/22/21.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA: COVID-19 case resulting in Hospitalization / Death. Patient received Moderna Vaccines on 1/13/2021 and 2/10/2021. Presented to ED on 8/31/2021 for weakness secondary to hyponatremia which is acute on chronic.  She was incidentally found to have COVID-19 infection.She was treated with stress dose Solu-Cortef.  During her 1st 24 hour, she started to show some desaturation.  She was started on dexamethasone 6 mg daily.  Patient continue showing no respiratory symptoms.  Her hypoxia did worsen slightly during her hospital stay and the maximum need of oxygen was 3-4 L.  Her examination showed no wheezes or rales.  And she has no respiratory symptoms. Patient was discharged on 9/4/2021. On 9/7/2021 presented to the ED with mild hypoxemia and shortness of breath. She was started on dexamethasone therapy and broad-spectrum empiric antibiotics with cefepime.  She received baricitinib from 9/8-12 but discontinued for suspected thrombosis. She continued to require increasing oxygen and ultimately on 09/17 intubated.  Blood culture and sputum culture have been negative respiratory pneumonia panel was negative, MRSA nasal swab negative.  She has been receiving Unasyn for possible aspiration pneumonia. Unfortunately, she continued to progressively worsen developing renal failure with multi-system organ failure, acidosis, hyperkalemia, and refractory shock on multiple pressors. On 9/21 patient's family elected for comfort care. Patient expired 9/21/2021.
LAB_DATA: Positive COVID-19 test on 8/31 and 9/7 using the Roche LIAT SARS assay platform using PCR or equivalent Nucleic Acid  Amplification(NAA)technology.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within a few minutes I started feeling lightheaded. It started to turn in some dizziness. They let us wait for about 15-20 minutes but I was not feeling better so I asked for more time. Then my heart started beating faster and I felt my breathing was kind of shallow. I wanted to go to home because I was not feeling good. As I was walking out, the front desk nurse told me I looked very pale so they took me back. They took my blood pressure and it was elevated. My blood pressure shot up maybe 20 points and my heart was beating fast. I stayed there for about 3 hours. They let me go home when my blood pressure went down. It took 3 hours to go down, I felt uncomfortable for the next hours.  I was very tired and I had some headaches. I still feel like my breathing is shallow. The first days were difficult to work as usual. As the days went on I started feeling better. My doctor was fully aware since he works at the place where I got the shot. I am still dealing with lot of dizziness since that night. I am planning on seeing a specialist for that.
OTHER_MEDS: Lamotrigine, Sertraline, Proair, Advair, Montelukast, Nurtec for migraines, Emgality monthly

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 3 days after received the Moderna vaccine I started to get sharp pains on the left side in my chest, it kept coming and going. I didn't think too much of it and thought it could be from gas possibly. As the days went on I kept feeling this pain and then it started to feel like I had gas trapped in the chest. By Monday, September 20, 2021 the chest pains would not go away and it started to worry me. My mid week of that week I called a Cardiologist to schedule and appointment and it was scheduled for two weeks out.  By Friday, September 24, 2021 I was still having the sharp chest pains that would not go away, I'm a healthy 34 year old and have no underlying health issues and a high immunity. After the sharp chest pains on the morning of Friday, September 24 around 9:00 am I started to have pain go towards my inner shoulder and then tingling and numbness down my left arm, my fingers began to go numb and tingling. I began to worry and thought I may be having a heart attack. I decided to go the  ER & Urgent Care to have it checked out by doing an Xray of my chest. The doctor saw to heart inflammation and didn't say what it could be, but ever since then I constantly have random chest pains with nerve pain going down my left arm. I've never had this in my life, until after I received the 1st dose of the Moderna vaccine - 3 days after the vaccine.  I am afraid to get my 2nd dose of the Moderna since my reaction can be even worse.
Pericarditis
LAB_DATA: Blood test, chest xrays, echocardiogram,  cath lab

On 9/21/2021 at approximately 9:45 PM I started feeling a lot of pressure in the middle of my chest and both arms upper and lower also had painful pressure.  I walked around a bit and drank some water to see if the discomfort would pass.  It did not and my girlfriend drove me to a medical facility 5 minutes away.  There the ER doctor had blood drawn and performed an EKG.  The EKG was good as was the blood.  Since my symptoms were indicative of a heart attack, Doctor wanted another blood test performed ~3 hours following the first.  The second test indicated an ellevated Troponin level at which point arrangements were made to transport me to the hospital. I arrived at the ER ~4:30AM.  There more blood tests were performed as was another EKG.  At some point I was moved to an ICU room.  A doctor poke to me informing me that I had suffered a mild heart attack.  By 4:30 PM the afternoon of 9/22/2021 another doctor  was performing a cathetarization in an attempt to clear the blockage.  Somewhere in there it was determined my LAD had a blockage.
LAB_DATA: Doctor ultimately did perform a cathetarization placing two stents where the LAD blockage (09/23/2021).  He did a fantastic job!!!!

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Admission to critical care hospital with COVID-19 diagnosis on admission
hospitalization (non-ICU)

42-year-old lady with a history of obesity who was recently admitted to outside hospital with COVID-19 pneumonia and associated complications including acute hypoxemic respiratory failure, ARDS, and AKI.  During the course of her hospitalization, she was treated with dexamethasone, remdesivir, tofacitinib, Plaquenil, and ivermectin.  She required intubation on 9/10 and developed cardiac arrest after a prolonged period of hypoxia on 9/12.  She was transferred for higher level care and treatment with CRRT.  She had a vascular catheter placed on 9/15 initiated dialysis that same night.  She had an echocardiogram on 9/15 that most notably showed RV was mildly dilated with moderately reduced function therefore she was started on therapeutic heparin given the concern for possible PE in the setting of Covid.  Patient underwent dialysis again on 9/17.  Lower extremity Dopplers were negative for DVTs on 9/16. From a respiratory standpoint, she is being treated with flolan and has been continued on zosyn and zyvox since admission. She was started on voriconazole on 9/17 and fungal labs (fungitel, galactomannan, blaso/histo Ag) were ordered for concern of possible underlying fungal infection. CT PE studay showed two RV thrombus. Therapeutic heparin was changed to argatroban to reduce fluid intake.  Unfortunately, despite our best efforts including maximizing ventilator settings and multiple rounds of hemodialysis patient continued to decline without improvement.  After discussion with family on 9/22 decision was made to transition patient to comfort care but to keep her on the ventilator.  On the morning of 9/23 at 0655 patient lost pulse and was pronounced dead.
Real Puffy Face, Excessive Sweating, Severe Fatigue, Extreme Agitation, Fluctuating Fever, Nausea, Debilitating Headaches, afraid.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediate Rxns:  Both injections I had the typical soreness at the injection site.  I reacted more adversely to the 2nd dose:  Much more swelling & pain at the injection site (size of a walnut), the next day I had fever of 100.6, body aches and chills, had to go to bed for the rest of the day after the injection.  Felt tired for a couple days, but all in all, not that bad.  I knew the reaction was a sign of actual immunity being built up, so I have no complaint.  Two adverse physical rxns a couple months after the shots:  1) I think I got a mild case of Covid toes mid-March through April, and was completely gone by early May.  I did not have any new shoes, and I do not get swelling of the cuticles or bruising like this was.  It progressed from painful red swelling to dark red, purplish to almost black small blood blisters before it resolved.  Never had that before.  I did not see a physician for it.  I saw pictures of mild cases on the internet and didn't think it was of much consequence.  2)  In April, 2021 I suddenly developed a very stiff left jaw that for a couple weeks made crunchy sounds.  The cracking stopped, but the joint became very painful all the way up into the left ear and my ability to open my mouth was much decreased.  I couldn't bit down on tough to chew food.  I didn't have good insurance coverage at the time, so I did not see a doctor about it.  The stiffness and radiating pain to my left ear jaw worsened over May & June, needed to take ibuprofen to handle the pain.  I figured it was TMJ - and can be related to stress which of course we all have through this pandemic.   I got Medicare in July, so I consulted my dentist and an ENT about it, but decided not to do a bite guard because I do not grind my teeth at night.  Interestingly, the symptoms have lessened since early August and I am almost back to normal now.  Seems the TMJ was temporary.
Admitted to Hospital on Date of Adverse Event [recorded in VAERS] for treatment of Covid-19 Positive following completion of Covid Vaccine Series
Pleural effusion, pneumonia
OTHER_MEDS: Prempro, senior mutivitamins, magnesium, calcium, zinc, biotin, vitamin c, probiotics, flaxseed

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Admission to critical care hospital with COVID-19 diagnosis on admission

The first day there was just the usual small red welt at the injection site. Nothing unusual on day two, same as the first two shots, red welt at injection site with tenderness.  On the third day, which was Wednesday,  the red welt now extended out 5 inch circle but nothing else from injection site.    Thursday started the rash on my tummy and from then on continued to crop up on different parts of my body with intense itching, small blisters and some areas of angry red welts.  By Sunday morning  it reached a crescendo with me, intense rashes now all over my torso, behind my knee, upon my shoulder and backside.  Contacted Pfizer and they took a report and gave us a incident report # U8NA0WZM.  I researched online and found out that one of the side affects of the vaccine is a rash usually on first or second dose.  Since this is new...booster shot....no information was available. The itching and pain was very intense so I took Benadryl tablets and Benadryl gel to relieve some of the intense itching.    We could literally follow the path of the vaccine as blisters and rash started on the left side of the body and each day proceeded down and then around to the right side of the body, the right side not being as severe as the left side.  Woke up this morning, Monday September 27th  and found two new small areas that cropped up on my leg and arm on the right side .  Contacted our primary care doctor this morning and emailed her pictures of the rash to get her opinion and to keep them recorded in my files.  Waiting for a call back from primary doctor.
I got shingles on my back.

Approx 4 weeks later the same reaction occurred, more severely this time and I was put on the same routine of medicines, but at a higher dose of medicine.  I was on this from August to September 17th.  I was put in intensive care ICU due to adverse reactions to DAPSONE and had sepsis shock, and organ failure when I arrived to the hospital.  Still under doctor care.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Seemed to be more painful than usual almost immediately and gradually worsened. By around 10:00PM I had a low grade fever, muscle aches, and arm was severely sore. Could not lift high enough to even view the watch on my wrist. The next morning I woke up and still had a fever - I had not connected at that point that it could be from the vaccination so I actually went and had a Covid test done (was negative). My shoulder area continued to have great pain and I had almost no range of motion in that arm. I went to a routine doctor visit on 9/8 and mentioned to the nurse (who happened to be the same person who administered the vaccination) and she said I was probably just sore because I am small in stature. (I am 5'2", normally around 120-125 lbs.) I tried to "push through it" and hoped it would get better. After it continued to bother me and wake me all through the nights, I emailed my doctor on 9/9 to let her know something did not feel normal. On 9/10 I went back to Health where she indicated I may have frozen shoulder. Xrays were performed and she massaged my arm to get it moving a little more. After this I had bruising from my shoulder to my elbow, but my range of motion was better. As of today, I can move my arm much more but still have to modify movements at the gym and still have pain in my shoulder - especially when I lift my arm directly above my head - it is painful. Have also contacted MN Dep't of Health several times throughout this process but no one has been able to connect me to the correct person and my voicemail was never returned. I heard about VAERS after inquiring on social media if anyone else had this happen after a vaccination administered in the arm.
LAB_DATA: Doctor visit and xray ray mentioned above on 9/10, which my doctor said showed nothing unusual.

Fewer hives visible, and those seen are noted to be smaller and less raised. She was diagnosed with COVID on 8/2 at her PCP's office.  She has felt progressively worse -- noting SOB, cough, myalgias, and weakness -- since about 8/1.  She was vaccinated in March 2021 (received both Pfizer vaccines at Pharmacy).  She had presented today to receive Regeneron infusion; however, she was noted to be tachypneic.  SpO2 there was 81% on room air.  She was sent to the ER for evaluation.  ABG noted hypoxemia with PO2 45.  She was placed on 3 L supplemental oxygen with improvement of her SpO2 -- she is not on oxygen at baseline.  CXR consistent with viral pneumonia and emphysematous changes/COPD.  She denies a history of COPD, never smoker, no secondhand exposure, etc.  Not on inhalers at baseline.  Labs noted leukocytosis, normocytic anemia, thrombocytosis, hypokalemia.  With concern for COVID pneumonia, she was admitted to the inpatient service for continued workup and management.  She was admitted to the COVID step-down unit and started on dexamethasone and remdesivir.  We noted interval clinical improvement, fortunately.  Her oxygen requirement was titrated down to 2 L.  She qualified for home oxygen and case management made these arrangements.      Patient was found to have microcytic anemia.  She denied any known history of anemia and also denied any abnormal bleeding or bruising.  We tried to obtain a Hemoccult but no sample was provided.   Of note, she already had an appointment with physician later this month for a diagnostic colonoscopy.  We strongly recommended that the patient follow up with this appointment.  Emphysematous changes were also noted on the patient's imaging.   She had no known history of COPD and was a lifelong nonsmoker.   She denied any smoking exposure, either.  We recommend continued outpatient surveillance.   She should continue to follow-up with her nephrologist regarding her CKD.

Since the patient had an anaphylactic reaction previously doctor premidicated the patient with acetaminophen 2x 325mg PO ONCE, diphenhydramine 25mg PO ONCE, and loratadine 10mg PO ONCE half-hour (1:30 pm) prior to getting the vaccine dose. The patient received the 2nd dose at 2:00 pm and was stable for a half-hour after receiving the vaccine. Around 2:30 pm she started to feel itchy and felt a choking sensation so she administered her on EpiPen. Due to this, the patient was evaluated by a full code rapid response team and referred to ER. In ER she was diagnosed with an acute allergic reaction to vaccination with complete resolution.  The patient felt better while she was in ER and was monitored for another half-hour prior to discharge.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am a breastfeeding mother to a 10 month old infant. I received vaccine on 9/1/21 and about 12 hours later (9/2/21) developed fever, headache, body aches and soreness at the injection site. On 9/3/21 my baby developed a fever, fussiness, and decreased appetite and this continued until 9/7/21. He also developed diarrhea on 9/6/21. He was seen at his pediatrician's office on 9/7/21 and they could find nothing wrong (CBC was normal, COVID negative, ears clear) and said he probably had a viral infection that was resolving. He did not have fever the morning of 9/7/21. The fever returned that evening and continued the rest of the week as well as the fussiness and decreased appetite- I took him back to the pediatrician on 9/10/21 and they could again find nothing wrong (this was day 8 of fever > 101). On the morning of 9/11/21 he became inconsolable and was running a fever of 102.1 and I took him to the emergency room at Hospital. They did more intensive lab work, x-ray, respiratory panel and it only showed atelectasis vs. early pneumonia in his lung and they decided to treat with antibiotic and nausea medication.  He continued to breastfeed for the duration of his illness, as it was the only way the he would take fluid
LAB_DATA: 9/7: CBC (normal); COVID test (negative) 9/11: CBC (normal), Resp viral panel (negative); chest x-ray (atelectasis vs. early pneumonia)

Headaches began coming with much more frequency and intensity. Went and saw my PCP on 5/7/2021. She was concerned by the length of the headache without relief (it had been almost 1.5 weeks of a severe headache with no relief at this point, so she called in for me to have MRI). Pain intensified and become constant and excruciating. Ended up in the ER two times on 5/11 and 5/12. Pain was so severe I couldn't function, sleep, or eat. It felt like my head was going to explode and was WAY worse than natural childbirth, which I have gone through 3 times. Had CT Scan with contrast, normal results. Sent home with strong pain meds and gave referral to neurologist. Saw 2 neurologists they have high dose pain meds for me to take. These did help the headache slightly better but gave me stomach issues. Had MRI on 5/17, with normal results. Over the next month relied on family to help my family survive, as I mostly laid in bed. Finally began to feel better and was able to slowly wean off strong meds. Now I have sporadic headaches which are still out of the norm for me but not as intense as the May ones.

On Day 1 -9/10/21  following my first dose of Pfizer I experienced tingling and numbness down my right arm that reached to my fingers but I didn't think much of it due to a similar sensation I had in the past from a rhomboid injury.   On Day 3 - 9/13/21  I began to experience twitching under my right eye. On Day 4 - 9/14/21  The twitching continued but progressed into tingling and numbness on the right side of my face.  I also developed a rash on both of my cheeks. On Day 5 - 9/15/21 The symptoms continued to be present and I began to feel the tingling in numbness in my right arm again so I was advised to go to Urgent Care where it was confirmed that I was experiencing inflammatory neuropathy and likely a result from the vaccine. I was prescribed Prednisone at 20 mg to be taken twice orally for 3 days.  Symptoms began to subside following my first dose but fully returned by the end of my prescription. On day 10 - 9/20/21  I went to see a neurologist, because my symptoms were still ongoing.  By this time the spasms and numbness and tingling in my legs had not yet presented itself.  Dr diagnosed me with an autoimmune inflammatory response to the vaccine. On day 11 - 9/21/21  My symptoms progressed to the top of my head on the right side and both of my legs, very faintly on the left leg and predominantly more noticeable on the right leg and eventually only noticeable on the right leg.  It felt as if my legs were asleep and the right leg felt very weak as if I could fall at any moment. I also started to experience involuntary muscle spasms in my right leg and throughout the right side of my body (upper body and ribcage).   The symptoms have been ongoing to date 9/27/21
LAB_DATA: The following lab results were ordered by Dr.  and  resulted on 9/24/2021 Erythrocyte Sedimentation C- Reactive Protein Ana Reflex Profile Vitamin B12 TSH Reflex MRI of Brain -- scheduled for 9/29/2021
OTHER_MEDS: Medrol dose pack 4mg - last dose taken on 9/6/2021

Almost Immediate tingling from Left elbow down to pinky and ring fingers. Same sensation of being hit on the funny bone. The tingling was at higher intensity for about 10 days before dying down to a 3/10 pain level. In the meantime there was also minimal swelling in the elbow, outside area. I can name 5 nights where I was awoken from an increase in tingling levels and had to take advil to bring it down. Its more uncomfortable than painful. After 4 weeks I got a massage to try to move things around. Tingling died down but soreness is still present almost 6 weeks later.  Background - 12 years ago I dislocated that left elbow and tore the UCL. I never got surgery on it. On occasion it is sore or swells due to 100% humidity levels in the air or excessive weight training. It has never tingled though since the initial injury which is more cause for concern than anything. My second shot was given in my right arm. As of today, the tingling is a 1/10 in pain, just enough to be present but the soreness in elbow is there. The best description I can give this feeling is exhaustion. I feel as though I've been lifting weights with it, but I haven't.

Hospitalized 9/20/2021; COVID-19 positive 9/16/2021; fully vaccinated  DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Hypoxia [R09.02] Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus [U07.1, J12.82]   HOSPITAL COURSE: The patient is a 82 y.o. male with Hx of DM type 2, prostate cancer, CKD 3, atrial fibrillation on Coumadin, and HTN who presented to ED with complaints of worsening shortness of breath. His symptoms started 9/13 and included shortness of breath, cough, fatigue, and decreased appetite. He developed fever of 101.9 on 9/16 and had a positive COVID-19 test from pharmacy on 9/16. He was vaccinated with the J&J vaccine in 3/21.   In the ED, he was tachypneic and hypoxic at 88% on room air. He was placed on 2L NC with improvement in oxygen saturation. His labs were notable for sodium 130, bicarbonate 19, BUN 22, creatinine 1.18, WBC 14, INR 1.9. Chest x-ray showed bilateral pneumonia.  He received decadron 6 and remdesivir. His O2 requirements initially increased to 6L via nasal cannula, but gradually improved. Per pulm rehab he required 1L at rest and 3.5L with activity on the day of discharge. PT/OT recommended home with assist. The patient's hyponatremia improved. His glucose was elevated while on steroids, but decadron was not continued on discharge and he returned to his home medication regimen.   The patient has been enrolled in the COVID at home program and will have visiting nurse services. I have recommended he have an INR drawn 9/28 and that he follow up with the anticoagulation clinic at DC. The patient was discharged home in stable condition with home O2.

Chief Complaint  pt illness since 8/10, covid + fatigue, lightheaded, cough, shortness of breath, fever, chills, BA, HA, loss of taste or smell. nausea, recieved monoclonal antibodies last week. O2 sat 88% History of Present Illness: patient is a 68-year-old man with a history of CAD (s/p CABG), RA, hypertension, and DMII who presented to the ED with worsening shortness of breath in the setting of COVID-19 infection.   The patient developed fatigue and URI symptoms around 8/11. He tested positive for COVID on 8/11. He was able to be arranged to have monoclonal antibody treatment on 8/12.  Patient reports that since his monoclonal antibody treatment that he has continued to have ongoing fatigue.  He  has also had ongoing cough, fever,  and body aches.  Patient was seen by his PCP on day of presentation and reportedly had oxygen saturations in the high 80's.  Patient was then instructed to present to the ED for further evaluation.  The patient was admitted to the COVID step-down unit.  He received 5 days of remdesivir and dexamethasone.  The patient was initially on 4 L, but quickly over the last several days we have been able to wean him down significantly really to almost room air.  Today, the patient has actually gotten to room air, but when he gets up, he does desaturate with ambulation.  His creatinine was slightly elevated when he was admitted, his ARB was held because his blood pressure was a little soft.  His creatinine went from 1.3 down to 1.1 upon discharge.  Also, his platelet count was slightly low when he was admitted, which is fairly common with COVID-19.  His platelet count was initially 108, but on the day of discharge it had already rebounded to 148.    He is eating and drinking.  He had had a bowel movement, which is not  uncommon for him.  He has struggled with constipation at home. He is eating and drinking.  He had had a bowel movement, which is not  uncommon for him.  He has struggled with constipation at home.    In terms of his diabetes, the patient was taken off his Jardiance and his glipizide along with his metformin while he is in the hospital.  Obviously, he had some elevation of his glucose, is related to the dexamethasone.  I think that will probably resolve itself after he finishes tape his dexamethasone course.   The patient feels well.  He qualified for 1-2 L of oxygen mostly when he ambulates.  He did get down to 86, when he ambulated.  I basically outlined him that he will probably need it for 1-2 weeks.  He will be discharged in markedly improved condition.  His diet should be heart healthy.

Patient presents with cough, fever, tachycardia and hypoxia with symptoms concerning for COVID-19 pneumonitis. First does was on January 25th, 2021 (Pfizer, EL9262). Second dose was on February 19th, 2021 (Pfizer, EL9267). Felt fine with no issues until about 2-3 weeks later, a rash on my arm started to show up. It started circular in shape and was pearly white in the middle with a red on the outside of the circle and was raised like a welt. It started on the upper part of my arm and then spread across my shoulders and down my torso, but didn't go below my waist. My doctor said it was definitely a reaction to something. Right around the same time, they put me on a new medication (an anti depressant), so he told me to stop taking that and I did. It then continued to itch and the rash persisted for months and during that time, I went through two rounds of oral steroids and took multiple Benadryl a day to help with the itching and sort of quell the rash. I was then told I needed to see a dermatologist. When I saw them (this was 5 to 6 months post the initial reaction, they  only provided me some cream that didn't really work. Over the course of the first 1-4 months after the rash showed up (March to July), the rash changed from something looking like a mobilliform rash, to something that looked like shingles, then something that looked like pityriasis rosea, then eczema. But the time I got to the dermatologist, the worst of it had gone away. So she gave me a steroid shot and some cream (Triamcinolone Acetonide) and said if it didn't get better to call them back and they'd look at me again. I've called them but they haven't called me back, so I'm working with my PCP to see if they can refer me to someone else. I got my booster vaccine on August 20th, 2021 (Pfizer, EW0175) and now the rash is starting to return again, and I'm trying to get into my doctor but I am having difficulties doing so. Figured it would just go away, and it's persisted since the initial shots, but only in small places on my body. Currently, I have a breakout spot on my left bicep (close to the injection location), left hand, right forearm, my shoulders, neck, my right arm pit, and a small spot on my left hip.. The only two factors that changed during this past year was the COVID vaccine (which my booster is making it come back) and that new medication, which has been out of my system since march.
LAB_DATA: No tests were performed by my PCP, and when I was sent to my dermatologist they declined to run a biopsy or do bloodwork because they said it was eczema even though that doesn't run in my family and I've never had issues with my skin before my COVID vaccine.

On Monday I began taking magnesium and moringa pills once daily as supplements and took them consistently over the course of the week. On Wednesday, i woke up with extreme muscle soreness in my neck and shoulders and joints including my wrists. I had a headache and loss of appetite. I took Tylenol but felt feverish and the pain persisted so i slept all day except to walk my dog at 7am, 2pm and 8pm. I followed that schedule every day and the pain intensified on Thursday. As it got worse I started taking DayQuil and NyQuil as directed but was still getting worse. On Friday I began to have mucus buildup and phlegm and developed a cough and continued the DayQuil and NyQuil course. On Saturday the symptoms persisted but i was able to function by Saturday night with manageable symptoms as long as the DayQuil was working. On Sunday my symptoms had significantly decreased and I felt better but was unable to taste or smell anything. I stopped taking the DayQuil and NyQuil Sunday and my only symptoms were the loss of taste, smell, and I still sound congested when I talk. This pain was elevated evenings. This pain finally subsided in June 2021. I had soreness under my right arm which continued from my first Covid-19 vaccine from March 16, 2021. I still experience pain under my right arm. On May 3, 2021 at 10:45 am I experienced an episode of heartburn unlike any previously experienced. I am not prone to heartburn continued: This episode was so extreme that I had to stop at a pharmacy and purchase rolaids. My elevated heart rate continued and became quite alarming. On June 1, 2021 my heart rate was 143 just driving my car. I was seen by Dr. June 2, 2021. My blood pressure was high (without hypertension). The procedures I received included: A) Primary Procedure:Health Panel (Multiple Blood Tests) (General health panel This panel must include the following: Comprehensive metabolic panel Blood count, complete (CBC), automated and automated differential WBC count B) Primary Procedure:Fibrin D-dimer Test (Fibrin degradation products, D-dimer; quantitative). I also received an ECG. I was referred for a 24 heart monitor. This did not show any heart rhythm irregularities; however, my heart rate was a still a bit high. I have been monitoring my blood pressure since and it has steadily decreased to normal. On September 10, 2021 my blood pressure was 107/71. My heart rate has also improved steadily. Now when I am sitting it is in the 70's to 80's range. After the vaccines it was 105 to 112 just sitting.

He denied any headache, dizziness, chest pain.  Says  occasionally cough but does not bring up any sputum.  Denies any shortness of  breath.  No nausea, vomiting, or diarrhea.  His lab work however shows a  sodium of 112 with a baseline being around 132.  His potassium was 3.2.   Creatinine is normal at 1.1.  The patient also history of hypothyroidism, but  for some reason I do not see any Synthroid on his medication list and his TSH  is slightly high at 4.77 and a free T4 is a pending as we speak.  Chest x-ray  shows some patchy right-sided opacity, possible COVID-19 related pneumonia and  the patient was started on Rocephin and Zithromax and then the hospitalist  service was called for admission.  A nephrology consult was also obtained; and  because the patient has a change in mental status with a sodium of 112 he has  been started on 3% normal saline to be given 25 mL/h x10 hours only which is  250 mL, and we will do BMP and sodium q.4 hours. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had brain fogginess when I had COVID in November of 2020.  I was fine afterwards until I got the vaccine.  After the vaccine was administered, I had some blurry vision within an hour of getting it.  2 weeks later,  I started experiencing more brain fogginess than I had ever had, even during November when I previously had Covid.  There were times in June where I couldn't remember what I had for dinner, the night before and had to go to my dish washer to see what was in it to remind me.  There has been times at work when I'm on a mission to get stuff for stocking the rooms or times in procedures where I just go blank and can't remember things.  There was also a time in August when I had went away on the Lake for the whole weekend.  I woke up and was getting ready for work thinking about what I did on the weekend.  I could not even recall going away, let alone what we did while we were there.  I had to look at my phone's pictures to recall that.  A girl at work even noticed me being more forgetful than ever.  I do have some eye issues but seems like my vision has gotten a little worse as well.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: A couple days earlier, I was sensitive to really harsh smells. At first, it was just a tickle in my lungs  - an irritation. It started on the Tuesday before the 6th but only occurred once that day and then on Thursday it happened again. On the 6th, after I got my tooth pulled, I was knowing that my chest was bothering me. The next day, I could tell for sure it was my chest. I had been on Hydrocodone with the pulled tooth and so I only got a fever to 99. I never got to 100.4. When I did have a fever, it could have been from the anesthesia. It was never higher than 99. I started coughing and hacking and was worried about irritation from where the tooth was pulled. Wednesday, the 11th, I went to get the Rapid test. They told me I didn't have COVID - but it wasn't a PCR. On the 18th of August I had my PET scan - I told her I was sick when I was there for the scan. I am still coughing  - still can feel it in my chest and I can feel pain in one of my lungs (I don't have the coughing fits (like I had before) that I was still having last week). Before Labor day, (1st or 2nd) my Primary physician put me on  Erythromycin and a cough medicine pill and it stopped some of the congestion but it didn't stop the cough. Instead of hacking a lot, it reduced it - it was a lot less. Still have a cough but have recovered quite a bit. The CT scan will show if I'm recovered. (October 11th).
LAB_DATA: 18th of August - had a PET Scan (Radiology associates) - and I answered yes that I was feeling sick that day. Results of that said - There is new hyper metabolic ground glass opacity and nodular consolidation in the posterior right upper lobe of lung. It says no hyper metabolic pulmonary mass otherwise. What they said at the end of the review they said it likely could be pneumonia and she said she apologized to me, and she said that she hadn't realized that I was that sick and the PET results look like someone who had COVID. I am having a CT scan on October 11th.

Patient on BiPAP upon arrival, 90% FiO2 (60% FiO2 when she left at Moberly per transfer note). sx onset and diagnosis on 9/11, vaccinated with Moderna x2 in March. went to the ED at Moberly, sent home on 2 L O2. Returned on 9/15 for worsening symptoms, admitted. s/p Dexamethasone, Remdesivir, and a single dose of Tocilizumab there. s/p Rocephin, discontinued due to low inflammatory markers per OSH notes. OSH BLE doppler US negative for clots. No CT done per OSH records. CXR with Patchy bilateral airspace opacities, consistent with known COVID-19 Pneumonia. Superimposed pulmonary edema is within consideration. Remarkable admission labs: CRP wnl. procal 0.11.Ferritin, LDH, D-dimer elevated. Mild LFT elevation. Leukocytosis. LA 3.3 Cr 1.02. Potassium 5.2. Patient had PICC line placed 9/15 due to hard stick.  9/27: Due to persistent hypoxia despite BiPAP, patient was intubated on 9/27. She became hypotensive, believed to be distributive shock. Infectious work-up as noted below, initiated broad spectrum coverage for hospital acquired pneumonia and possible PJP given her underlying immunosuppression. Right sided radial arterial line placed, which was replaced with a right sided femoral arterial line after this line failed. The patient was paralyzed, received additonal INO treatment, received an esophageal balloon, and was proned on 9/27.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospitalization cough, vomiting, diarrhea, headache, and chills tested positive for COVID at HCF on 9/18.

I was hospitalized with pancreatitis on April 1st due to ongoing nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain. My AST/ALT were in the 1700s and I was admitted to manage the symptoms via morphine and IV fluids. I was discharged 3 days later, however, I still had ongoing nausea, vomiting, extreme weight loss, and reduced appetite. I was hospitalized again on June 6th due to similar symptoms and my liver function levels were in the 1400s again. According to a Physician, they believe my pancreatic episode was never resolved from April to June. They found a blockage and narrowing in my biliary duct, so a GI doctor placed a stent in my biliary duct. The stent was too small and ended up backing bile back into my body, making me worse, so they placed a larger stent (10cm). I still suffered from nausea and reduced appetite due to vomiting. I had the stent removed in August 2021 and they determined possible autoimmune hepatitis as an underlying issue and I am in the process of getting a liver biopsy currently.  The GI doctors do agree there could be a correlation from gallbladder issues due to a strong family history of gallbladder attacks (mother, maternal grandparents, and maternal uncle)
LAB_DATA: CT Scan, MRI, Abdomen X-ray - 04/21 CT Scan, MRI, 2 Endoscopy and 2 ERCPs, Stent placement - 06/21 ERCP / Stent Removal - 08/21 Liver Biopsy - Currently in process of being scheduled Gallbladder removal - Currently in process of being scheduled

I received the second Moderna vaccine on 9/24/21.  About an hour after receiving the vaccine, I started to get a sore arm and headache, this continued to worsen as the even progressed.  I awoke at 0530 on 09/25/21 (approximately 13 hours post vaccine) and was unable to move, it took 3 hours to get out of bed.  I was severely weak, lightheaded, dizzy, nauseous, severe muscle and bone aches, severe headache, SOB, and severe deltoid pain.  Once I was able to physically get myself out of bed, I was furniture surfing and barely able to walk.  I was extremely light headed and dizzy, and felt near syncope.  I rested in bed all day with these symptoms as well as extreme fatigue. I woke on 9/26/21, and felt generally better, however still had lightheadedness and dizziness with worsening SOB, and slight fatigue.  I attempted to do routine Sunday chores, but often had to rest due to worsening SOB and feeling lightheaded and dizzy.  I was able to shower, and noticed that my torso was covered in hives.  I proceeded to walk in care.  Upon arrival, walking from the care into the facility, I was quite SOB and my HR was 129.  I was brought into the room where I was able to sit.  After sitting my HR did decrease to 99.  I was treated with 60mg of PO prednisone.  Within one hour the hives, lightheadedness, dizziness, fatigue, HR and SOB had decreased.  Within 2 hours the SOB had resolved.  I was prescribed a regimen of prednisone and famotidine and instructed to purchase and take loratadine.  I did present to work on 9/27/21, however did have to take an extended break due to dizziness/lightheadedness and nausea.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Disclaimer:  Dates/descriptions are approximate.  This is a follow-up to my initial report filed back in April.    - Immediately after shot: heart rate spike to 180, dizziness, sweating, weakness and pain in hands ? sent to ER for monitoring; - 0-2 months after: Rapid heart rate for first two weeks; pain in extremities and limbs that ?traveled? upwards to hips, spine, and head; burning in mouth; severe headache and facial pressure; burning on scalp: tingling, burning, and numbness in various places on body; tongue pain and burning; feeling of ?manual? breathing; sudden flushing and HR spikes; deep pain?described as bone pain. Two more ER visits, multiple primary care visits, Rheumatology and Electrophysiology visits.  Bedridden for first two months;  medical leave required.  Labwork, X-rays, MRIs ordered.  Rheumatological / autoimmune cause ruled out.  - 2-4 months after: Bedridden; same symptoms plus ongoing muscle spasms and tremors; continuing, severe pain in spine, shoulders, knees.  Unable to tolerate physical therapy.  Additional doctor visits including Neurology visits.   Pain in chest and feeling of pressure on throat.  - 4-6 months out:  Continuing symptoms.  Able to get out of bed for longer periods of the day, but extreme muscle / exertional fatigue from activit.  Rapid HR continues, even at rest.  Dizziness and ?tunnel vision? upon standing.  Cardiology and Electrophysiology appointments; POTS suspected.  More Neurology visits?EMG/nerve conduction study, autonomic testing, and biopsies for small fiber neuropathy.   Echocardiogram, holter monitor.  Insignificant findings.  - 6-8 months :  Continued symptoms, but improving.  Rapid HR, dizziness, muscle fatigue/pain/weakness, unexplained rashes, tongue/mouth burning.  Continuing bone pain sensation.   Diagnosed with mast cell disorder by Allergist/Immunologist; advised that symptoms were a reaction to the vaccine.  Neuro treating heart issues as POTS.
LAB_DATA: Lab-work(blood, urine), EKGs, X-rays, MRIs, EMG, nerve conduction, holter monitor, echocardiogram, autonomic testing (QSART, sudomotor, tilt table test), three punch biopsies

My roommate and I got the COVID-19 Pfizer vaccine at about the same time. He got his the day before I did. A few days after the second dose, he started complaining about pneumonia. He went to the doctor to get antibiotics and steroids for it. The next day, I also got sick; but at the time I had no health insurance so I could not see a doctor about it. Symptoms: headache, sore throat, fatigue, dizziness, loss of appetite, fever, bad wet cough, pneumonia, shallow breathing, temporary loss of smell/taste, permanent reduction in sense of smell and muscle aches. Mainly symptoms were contained to the respiratory area. Usually if it's allergies the symptoms are mainly in my sinuses, but my head was clear this time. Starting on the second day after my vaccine (2nd dose), I had a bit of a sore throat and headache but didn't think too much of it.  It felt like I might be getting a "head cold" later, which happens a lot because of my seasonal allergies but they are typically not too bad and can be avoided by taking an antihistamine.  So I took a Benadryl when I got home. Then about two hours later I was having dinner in my kitchen, when all of a sudden it just hit me hard. A wave of fatigue and dizziness, followed by a long coughing fit. I could feel the fluid in my lungs along with the cough. I had to lie down or I likely would have passed-out. And within twenty minutes I had all the symptoms I previously listed. It stayed that bad for three days so I went to drive-through pharmacy and was tested for the COVID vaccine, results came back negative for that.  It stayed that bad for one more day after I got tested, then it gradually started to get a little bit better - at least the fatigue and dizziness weren't so bad and my sense of smell started coming back.  But I stayed sick for 11 days straight, had to "self-quarantine" because it was so bad. My immune system is stronger than average. I haven't even had the flu since I was seven (not for more than a day at least). It's so strong that it's attacking my own skin faster than the skin can heal now. It also results in having pretty serious allergies to tree pollen and pet dander. Usually illness that would make someone else sick for a whole week, I only get it for a day - maybe two days if it comes with digestive problems, too. So this is a very unusual experience for me to get sick like this. Literally it was so bad that I started to wish that someone would come in and just kill me.  The single most awful experience of my life. My roommate and I both got tested for the COVID-19 virus on the same day. We went to different branches of the pharmacy for the testing, and both got cleared with negative results. It could just be coincidental timing that my roommate and I both got some other respiratory infection just two days after the vaccine. I suspect it was more likely a result of the vaccine: reduced immune response, or increased susceptibility, or something like that.  I suspect as much partly because of the timing, but mostly because of the severity of it. I just never get sick like that. The fast onset of symptoms, the severity of symptoms, and the extended duration of it makes me think that either it is related to the vaccine, or we actually got COVID-19 but for some reason the contagion test didn't pick up on it. In addition, after both doses (worse after the second one) I had a lot of pain and swelling at/near the injection site.  I received the injections in my upper arms (one on each side) and most of the arm was very stiff and sore after each injection for two days for the first dose and three days for the second dose, starting early on the day after the injection. I apologize for the delay in getting this form done.  I've been meaning to do it since I got sick but I just kept getting distracted by other things and I'd forget about it, then remember again when I'm too busy to sit down and finish the paperwork so I'd forget again.
LAB_DATA: COVID-19 test (negative result) - tested on or about 07/02 (I think), at the same facility where I received the vaccine.
ALLERGIES: Digestive allergies: Sulfates, ginger, oxy/hydrocodone, seasonal respiratory allergies (tree pollen mostly)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the first COVID-19 (Pfizer-BioNTech) on 4/7/21 from occupational health at my workplace.   I stayed approximately 15 minutes after my injection.  Then I drove home, which took approximately 20 minutes.  When I got home, I urinated.  After I wiped, there was bright red bleeding from my vagina on the tissue that I used to wipe myself.  That was the first episode of breakthrough bleeding. I was menstruating at my normal monthly time when I got my second dose of the vaccine.  Because I was menstruating, identifying breakthrough bleeding was impossible.  I had breakthrough bleeding (vaginal) again in May 2021, June 2021, July 2021, August 2021, and September 2021.  All days of the breakthrough bleeding occurred between days 11-18 of my menstrual cycle.  My time of menstruation is consistent as I am taking Yasmin and has been consistent for many years.  I have been taking Yasmin for at least 10 years.  Before I received the COVID-19 vaccine, I would normally menstruate  on days 1-6 or days 1-7 of my cycle and have no breakthrough bleeding.  Since I received the COVID-19 vaccine, I have had breakthrough bleeding every month on days that are not on days 1-6 or 1-7 of my cycle.  The breakthrough bleeding is dark brown.  The bleeding begins as a moderate amount and then lightens to mild and then stops.
LAB_DATA: None. I will have my first OB-GYN appointment since receiving the COVID-19 vaccine on October 1, 2021.
