SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was 5 weeks postpartum and still trying to establish breastfeeding/milk supply. After my second dose of the COVID vaccine, I woke up with intense chest pain. Over the course of a few hours, I realized that the lymph nodes in my chest/breasts were inflamed. This caused extreme clogging of my milk ducts, and my milk supply dropped dramatically. I was primarily pumping breastmilk at the time, so I could see the exact output, and I was pumping about 1/2 to 2/3 of my usual output. The clogs were extremely painful and persistent. It took about 5 days for them to fully resolve and over a week for my milk supply to get back up to capacity. I?d recommend that any breastfeeding individuals wait until after 12 weeks postpartum (generally when milk supply is regulated) to get vaccinated in the event that their milk supply is affected like mine was.

I went to imaging center on September 20 for an already scheduled ultrasound and mammogram.  It was alarming because in September 2020 I was diagnosed with breast cancer, stage 0. At 1635 client reported feeling "she could not take deep breaths." PHN informed paramedics would be called for further assessment and client declined. At 1636 client stated, "it is all gone." SYMPTOM_TEXT: After the vaccine, the client reported that her arm felt "numb" to Lead Ancillary and she stated that "I didn't feel the shot." The client then reported feeling "high" to lead Ancillary. Lead Ancillary notified RN and RN, who then responded to the client. The client reported feeling, "Like I'm on a cloud and dizzy." RN asked if the client's vision was clear, and the client reported "You're a little foggy." The client was sitting in an office chair with her right leg elevated. The client had a boot on her right foot and a right knee brace from a previous injury. The client denied any history of syncope. The client reported a history of hypertension, which is not controlled with medication. The client stated that she has recently been taking Ibuprofen for pain, but did not take any ibuprofen today. The client has no known allergies. Vitals obtained at 7:27PM were as follows: HR 105 and automatic BP 136/80. The client also reported feeling "cold and shaky." RN felt the client's hands which felt cool. RN did not see any visible shaking of the client's hands or body. The client reported a stomach ache. The client last ate a salad at 3:00PM. Respiration rate was 16 per minute at 7:30PM. The client began eating a personal protein bar at 7:31PM. The client stated that "It's helping to eat, the fog is kind of going away." RN arrived on scene. Repeat vitals obtained at 7:38PM were as follows: automatic BP 132/77, HR 82, and O2 99%. The client was alert and oriented to person, place, time, and situation. The client reported that she was still "cold," that her vision was clear, mild dizziness, and feeling tired. The client denied any s/s of anaphylaxis. RN assessed the client's skin near the vaccination site. RN noted redness about 2 inches below where the vaccine was administered, that was approximately 1 inch long and 0.5 inches wide. The client denied any itching at the site and stated she had not seen that red spot before. RN noted no other signs of redness or a rash across the client's neck, chest, or arms. Repeat vitals obtained at 7:47PM were as follows: BP 138/83, HR 88, O2 99%. The client stated "I feel like I drank wine. I feel tired, and cold." The client also reported that her vision was "foggy in areas." The client reported that she was "starting to feel a little headache." The client denied any pain associated with the headache. The client was continuing to eat her protein bar. The client stated that when the vaccine was administered, "I felt like it went all through my body." The client reported persistent feeling "foggy and dizzy." The client reports a history of dizziness after not eating for a while. The client reported "weakness" while trying to open her bottle of water. RN assisted the client and opened the water bottle. At 7:52PM the client was drinking water provided to staff. At 7:55PM the client reported feeling "dizzy after I use energy." The client stated that the cold feeling was "going down, and I'm still a little shaky." Vitals obtained at 7:58PM were as follows: BP 125/79, HR 83, and O2 97%. The client reported that she still felt dizzy and tired. She stated "I feel like I'm in slow motion." The client denied any foggy vision spots, but stated that the "fog is in my head." The client stated she did not drive to the vaccination site, and called someone to come and pick her up. At 8:04PM the client stated that she needed to use the restroom. The client stood up without assistance, placed her right knee on her knee walker, and began ambulating with the use of the knee walker to the restroom. The client reported she felt, "A little dizzy standing." RN accompanied the client to the restroom. The client returned from the restroom and sat in the anti-gravity chair. RN  and RN reclined the anti-gravity chair to a semi-fowler's position. Vitals obtained at 8:09PM were as follows: BP 122/75, HR 81, O2 98%, and RR 18. The client reported a stomach ache and nausea and requested to sit up. The anti-gravity chair was adjusted to a high fowler's position. The client reports a history of anxiety and states that she experiences dizziness with her anxiety. RN offered to activate EMS due to the client's persistent symptoms and the client declined. RN discussed options for the client including activating EMS or going to urgent care on her own.  The client stated that sometimes she goes to the pharmacy to check her "blood sugar." The client stated her plan after leaving the vaccination site was to go to the pharmacy to get her blood glucose checked, and that she would go to urgent care if her blood glucose was high. The client denied any persistent nausea or stomach ache. RN educated the client regarding s/s of anaphylaxis, when to seek EMS, and V-Safe. The client voiced understanding of this education. The client stated, "Okay, I want to leave." The client stood up with the assistance of her scooter, placed her knee on the knee walker. The client ambulated with the use of the knee walker outside of the building and stated that someone was picker her up. RN accompanied the client outside the vaccination site, and visualized the client ambulate with the use of the knee scooter off of the property at 8:30PM. RN did not visualize the client get into a vehicle.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On the second evening post injection I experienced tightening, fullness and heaviness in my throat, air hunger, chest tightness/heaviness,  chest pain and palpitations/irregular heart beats, anxiety, increase thirst and urination from 8pm to 3:30 am. The symptoms resolved enough by 3:30 so that I could fall asleep. I have an epi pen with me left from when I used to have severe allergies regularly (a condition I have healed form over the last 1.5 years following removing myself from the mold exposure). I considered going to the ER but waited. On day 3 I began taking antihistamines for 7 days - Claratin which helped take the edge off the 3rd and 4th night. I am now taking half a claratin but still experiencing slight symptoms at night, airway, chest tightness, insomnia. Mast cells have a circadian rhythm which I think is why it's worse at night. I truly hope it fades because I have made tremendous progress on my health and this feels like a set back.

ALLERGIES: Severe allergy to mold. I experienced four years of exposure and was unaware it was it cause of my severe allergy till the end of the 4th year. I took anti-histamines and Cromolyn Sodium for the latter 2 years.

Extremely faint; Sweating profusely; Blurred vision /seeing white; Felt like she was going to drop to floor; Right foot felt as if it was tingling; Tip of toe of right foot felt numb/felt numbness starting from ankle to toe; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of SYNCOPE (Extremely faint) in a 54-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch no. 939906) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     No Medical History information was reported.    On 02-Sep-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) 1 dosage form. In September 2021, the patient experienced PARAESTHESIA (Right foot felt as if it was tingling) and HYPOAESTHESIA (Tip of toe of right foot felt numb/felt numbness starting from ankle to toe). On an unknown date, the patient experienced SYNCOPE (Extremely faint) (seriousness criterion medically significant), HYPERHIDROSIS (Sweating profusely), VISION BLURRED (Blurred vision /seeing white) and PRESYNCOPE (Felt like she was going to drop to floor). At the time of the report, SYNCOPE (Extremely faint), HYPERHIDROSIS (Sweating profusely), VISION BLURRED (Blurred vision /seeing white) and PRESYNCOPE (Felt like she was going to drop to floor) outcome was unknown and PARAESTHESIA (Right foot felt as if it was tingling) and HYPOAESTHESIA (Tip of toe of right foot felt numb/felt numbness starting from ankle to toe) had not resolved.        The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Unknown) was unknown.       Concomitant medications was not provided. Treatment medications was not reported.   After 1 or 2 days of vaccination, her right foot felt as if it was tingling. Her tip of toe of right foot felt numb. Starting from ankle to toe she felt numbness. It was still there. It would not go away. Patient donated blood on Tuesday. After donation of blood despite fact that she had eaten lunch and had several glasses of water, patient became extremely faint. She was at a bookstore sat in a chair and started sweating profusely. She started having blurred vision and saw white and felt like patient was going to drop to floor. It was so scary and she had never experienced this before. The only thing that saved her was drinking cold water and after 30 minutes she could finally stand up & walk out the door. The patient was a healthy person with no underlying health issues and she did not take any medications. She deeply regret getting this vaccine because ever since she got the vaccine, her right foot felt dead - numb & tingling. She was told that she should go to primary care physician and get tests. At the time of this report, the patient was still experiencing numbness and tingling in her right foot and did not had time to go to the physician. She was just very unhappy that she got this vaccine because she had never had side affects to any vaccine like this. She was very discouraged by side affects associated with the vaccine, to the point that she was extremely reluctant to get her second dose.  Company Comment: This case concerns a 54-year-old, female patient with no relevant medical history, who experienced the unexpected event of syncope same day after blood donation The event occurred approximately 12 days after the first dose of Moderna Covid-19 vaccine. The rechallenge was not applicable, as the event happened after the first dose. The event was considered related to the product per the reporter's assessment. The benefit-risk continued in company comment section.   Most recent FOLLOW-UP information incorporated above includes: On 16-Sep-2021: Follow-up received on 16-Sep-2021 that contains Events added case is Upgraded to serious. On 24-Sep-2021: Follow up received is NNI.; Sender's Comments: This case concerns a 54-year-old, female patient with no relevant medical history, who experienced the unexpected event of syncope same day after blood donation The event occurred approximately 12 days after the first dose of Moderna Covid-19 vaccine. The rechallenge was not applicable, as the event happened after the first dose. The event was considered related to the product per the reporter's assessment. The benefit-risk relationship of Moderna Covid-19 vaccine is not affected by this report.

GALLBLADDER INFECTION (CHOLECYSTITIS); CHOLECYSTITIS INFECTIVE; BLOOD CLOT THATS ON THE TOP OF LIVER (THROMBOSIS); ANTICOAGULANT THERAPY; COVID-19 INFECTION; COLOSTOMY; INFECTION; SARS-COV-2 TEST POSITIVE; SUSPECTED CLINICAL VACCINATION FAILURE; BLOOD TEST ABNORMAL; PAIN; FEELING COLD; MALAISE; VOMITING; PYREXIA; BAD CASE OF ACID REFLUX (GASTROOESOPHAGEAL REFLUX DISEASE); This spontaneous report received from a health care professional via a Regulatory Authority Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) (VAER reference number 1582450) concerned a 63 year old male. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. No past medical history or concurrent conditions were reported. The patient experienced drug allergy when treated with codeine. The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, intramuscular, batch number: UNKNOWN) dose was not reported, 1 total administered to right arm on 03-JUL-2021 at 12:43 PM for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported. The Company is unable to perform follow-up to request batch/lot numbers. Concomitant medications included ascorbic acid/ergocalciferol/folic acid/retinol/tocopherol/vitamin. On 19-JUL-2021, the patient woke up at 5:30 am with a bad case of acid reflux which he had a while ago but not since he was taking prebiotics and probiotics which helped but not this time. He was vomiting and had a fever. He took Omeprazole that morning which has relieved it for a while but after eating some food it started all over again. The vomiting and fever was back with higher severity than before. By Wednesday, on 28-JUL-2021, it was better bad so he went over to a Medical Center for COVID-19 test which was was negative. They did ran a battery of blood work on him but after waiting for five long hours to be seen by a doctor he was extremely cold in the waiting area and he was in great pain sitting on the uncomfortable chairs. On 29-Jul-2021, The patient went over to urgent care and once again the PA give him another COVID- 19 test which was negative. The PA suggested the patient to visit over to a Hospital. On 30-Jul-2021, the patient went over there was tested again and was negative again. They checked him in but they never found the Covid-19 after being poked and stuck so many times he was really not feeling good and they did know that he had a inflamed and infected gallbladder which the infection traveled through his blood stream Which was very dangerous for him however it app eared that they were taking his blood every two hours which became very unbearable for him and he wanted to go home I went to pick him up at 3:00 am One of the call me to convince to still in the hospital but he refused. On 31-Jul-2021, the patient went over to another Hospital COVID test where he was found positive. The patient was diagnosed with COVID-19 infection (suspected clinical vaccination failure). All because his gallbladder was very inflamed and infected due to the vaccine and he also has a blood clot that was on top of his liver. The patient had to wear a colonoscopy bag until they can remove his gallbladder which was about four weeks. He had to wear the bag to drain any infection. He also administered with blood thinner (anticoagulant therapy). On an unspecified date, the patient was admitted to hospital. The patient was hospitalized for 7 days.  The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient had not recovered from anticoagulant therapy, blood test abnormal, covid-19 infection, gallbladder infection (cholecystitis), cholecystitis infective, colostomy, feeling cold, bad case of acid reflux (gastrooesophageal reflux disease), infection, malaise, pain, pyrexia, sars-cov-2 test positive, blood clot thats on the top of liver (thrombosis), and vomiting, and the outcome of suspected clinical vaccination failure was not reported. This report was serious (Hospitalization Caused / Prolonged). This report was associated with product quality complaint : 90000191544 The suspected product quality complaint has been confirmed to be the reported allegation could not be confirmed. A manufacturing related root cause could not be identified. Based on the Regulatory Authority evaluation/investigation performed. SYMPTOM_TEXT: DEATH; PULMONARY EMBOLISM; COVID-19; SARS-COV-2 TEST POSITIVE; VOMITING; DIARRHOEA; AUTOPSY; This spontaneous report received from a health care professional via a Regulatory Authority Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) (VAERS ID 1624304) concerned a 51 year old female patient of unspecified race and ethnic origin.   The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's concurrent conditions included: congenital adrenal hyperplasia, 21-hydroxylase deficiency, CVA (Cerebrovascular accident), white matter periventricular infarction, meningioma, lung nodule, hyperlipidemia, gastritis, gastroduodenitis, GI (Gastrointestinal) AVM (Arteriovenous malformation), GI bleed, melena, and diverticulosis, and the patient had no other current illness. The patient experienced drug allergy when treated with acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin), codeine, escitalopram, etodolac (Lodine), olanzapine (Zyprexa), Olanzapine and risperidone for unknown indication.  The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, and batch number: unknown, expiry: Unknown) dose was not reported, 1 total administered on 02-AUG-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported. The Company is unable to perform follow-up to request batch/lot numbers. Concomitant medications included calcium, denosumab (Prolia), dexamethasone, ergocalciferol (Vitamin D), lorazepam (Ativan), loxapine succinate (Loxitane), magnesium, omeprazole (Prilosec), potassium chloride, prazosin hydrochloride (Minipress), quetiapine fumarate (Seroquel) and sertraline hydrochloride (Zoloft) used for unknown indication.  On 03-AUG-2021, the patient experienced diarrhoea, vomiting (till 09-AUG-2021 and tested positive for COVID-19 (Coronavirus) via SARS-CoV-2 test. On the same day the patient experienced pulmonary embolism. On 09-AUG-2021, the patient was found dead at her residence. On an unspecified date in AUG-2021 an autopsy was performed, and pulmonary embolism was found to be the cause of death. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The outcome of death, pulmonary embolism, autopsy, covid-19, diarrhoea, vomiting and SARS-CoV-2 test positive was fatal. This report was serious (Death). SYMPTOM_TEXT: SYNDROME OF INAPPROPRIATE ANTIDIURETIC HORMONE; PSEUDOHYPONATREMIA; URINE TOXICOLOGY/ URINE DRUG SCREEN TEST POSITIVE FOR TETRAHYDROCANNABINOL; ATYPICAL GUILLAIN-BARRE SYNDROME; This spontaneous report was received from literature: Guillain-Barre Syndrome Presenting as Facial Diplegia after COVID-19 Vaccination: A Case Report. The Journal of Emergency Medicine. 2021 Aug 07;1-5. This report concerned a 38-year-old male of unspecified race and ethnic origin. The objective of this report was to describe a case of an atypical presentation of GBS (Guillain-Barre Syndrome) presenting with extremity paresthesias, dysarthria, and bilateral facial weakness in the absence of classic ascending limb weakness, and discuss differential diagnosis, triage, and management. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's concurrent conditions included: Anxiety, depression, alcohol user (average of 6 to 8 beers per day), and marijuana user (daily). The patient had been in a state of good health upon receipt of the vaccine 32 days prior. The patient received covid-19 vaccine adv26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: unknown, expiry: UNKNOWN) dose, start therapy date were not reported, 1 total administered for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported and has been requested. Concomitant medications included bupropion for anxiety and depression. On an unspecified date, approximately 2 weeks after vaccination, the patient experienced subacute, rapidly progressive, numbness and tingling in the tongue, lips, bilateral hands and feet/ paresthesias. Two days prior to presentation the patient began to develop difficulty moving his mouth, forming words/ dysarthria/slurred speech, bilateral facial weakness/ facial diplegia/bilateral facial nerve palsy in a lower-motor-neuron pattern with acral paresthesias variant and an absence of classic ascending limb weakness, as well as difficulty drinking from a straw and controlling the lips, cheeks and tongue while eating. The review of systems was notable for headaches, mild gait unsteadiness, generalized fatigue and dyspnea on exertion. The patient denied diplopia, dysphagia, or dysphonia, chest pain or palpitations, lightheadedness, fevers or chills, nausea, vomiting or diarrhea, urinary or bowel incontinence and falls or other trauma. The patient visited the emergency department in a clinically good condition, not in acute distress and was ambulating independently. Initial vital signs were as follows, blood pressure 218/80 mmHg, heart rate 85 beats/min, respiratory rate 16 breaths/min and oxygen saturation of 100%. The patient exhibited weak eye closure bilaterally and inability to smile or puff cheeks against resistance. The extraocular movements were intact and tongue was midline without fasciculations. Strength in the upper and lower extremities were intact (5/5) as sensation to light touch throughout. There was no dysmetria or gait ataxia. Deep tendon reflexes were reduced 1 plus in the lower extremities and only faintly present in the bilateral upper extremities. Laboratory data were notable for a white blood cell count of 12.25 x 10E3/mL with a normal differential, hemoglobin of 16.7 gram per deciliter, and a hematocrit of 49.5 L/L. The serum chemistries including liver function test, thyroid-stimulating hormone, folate, and B12 (Cobalamin), were all within normal limits. Urine toxicology/ Urine drug screen test was positive for tetrahydrocannabinol and covid-19 polymerase chain reaction was negative. A neurology consultation was obtained. The brain magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) with and without contrast and constructive interference in steady state (CISS) sequencing revealed focal enhancement of the bilateral internal auditory canal fundi which carried the CN-VII (cranial nerve) and CN-VIII and the bilateral cisternal segments of the trigeminal nerves. Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) analysis revealed glucose of 73 mg/dL, an elevated protein to 181 mg/dL, and 7 nucleated cells/high-power field (HPF; corrected for 2987 red blood cells/HPF), constituting albuminocytological dissociation suggestive of atypical Guillain-Barre syndrome. The electrodiagnostic evaluation was not performed as the CSF profile and clinical presentations were definitive of GBS. The patient was hospitalized and received intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) over 2 days to a total dose of 2 grams per kilo gram body weight, which showed a mild improvement in his symptoms. Measurements of negative inspiratory force was performed daily, and the patient had not developed any signs or symptoms of respiratory compromise. On hospital day 1, the patient developed new hyponatremia, which had reached a value of 124 mEq/L (milliequivalents per litre) during admission which was concluded to be multifactorial, attributed to pseudohyponatremia in the setting of IVIG as well as syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone in the setting of GBS. The patient was treated with fluid restriction and salt tabs with improvement in sodium to 134 mEq/L on discharge. The patient's symptoms showed no further progression and was discharged home on hospital day 4. The duration of hospitalization were 4 days. The discharge examination was notable for stable to improvement in bilateral facial weakness and dysarthria with generalized areflexia. The author concludes that the patient received the Johnson and Johnson vaccine against the COVID-19 virus 32 days prior to presentation. In the Johnson and Johnson COVID19 vaccine trial, one case of GBS in the post-vaccination arm was reported, however, there was also a case of GBS in the placebo arm. This did not imply a causal association between the Johnson and Johnson COVID-19 vaccine and GBS. Author cannot say definitively whether the patient's prior vaccination contributed to his development of GBS or was incidental to it. The risk of developing vaccine-associated GBS remains very low when viewed across the general population, and cases of GBS with a temporal association to vaccination are not necessarily caused by a vaccine-mediated immune response. Overall, the benefits of vaccination to prevent COVID-19 infection likely outweigh the risks of any potential adverse effects, including GBS, as stated in recent guidelines from the centers for disease control and world health organization. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient was recovering from syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone, pseudohyponatremia, and atypical Guillain-Barre syndrome, and the outcome of urine toxicology/ urine drug screen test positive for tetrahydrocannabinol was not reported. This report was serious (Hospitalization Caused / Prolonged).; Sender's Comments: V0: 20210941304-covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s- pseudohyponatremia, syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone, Urine toxicology/ Urine drug screen test positive for tetrahydrocannabinol. SYMPTOM_TEXT: CAT scan of my lungs on 16Sep2021, and it shows there was covid-19; congestive heart failure; irregular heart rate; fast pulse/ rapid pulse/ heart rate goes up; shortness of breath; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of CARDIAC FAILURE CONGESTIVE (congestive heart failure) in an 80-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 031M20A and 037K20A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     The patient's past medical history included Asthma (Occasionally, weather related, in the spring and the fall the patient would have asthma). Concurrent medical conditions included Sjogren's (autoimmune condition called Sjogren's) and Pulmonary hypertension. Concomitant products included LOSARTAN and AMLODIPINE for an unknown indication.   On 22-Jan-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 19-Feb-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. In February 2021, the patient experienced DYSPNOEA (shortness of breath). In March 2021, the patient experienced HEART RATE INCREASED (fast pulse/ rapid pulse/ heart rate goes up). On 19-Jun-2021, the patient experienced HEART RATE IRREGULAR (irregular heart rate). On 21-Jul-2021, the patient experienced CARDIAC FAILURE CONGESTIVE (congestive heart failure) (seriousness criteria disability and medically significant). On 16-Sep-2021, the patient experienced SUSPECTED COVID-19 (CAT scan of my lungs on 16Sep2021, and it shows there was covid-19). At the time of the report, CARDIAC FAILURE CONGESTIVE (congestive heart failure), HEART RATE INCREASED (fast pulse/ rapid pulse/ heart rate goes up) and DYSPNOEA (shortness of breath) had not resolved and HEART RATE IRREGULAR (irregular heart rate) and SUSPECTED COVID-19 (CAT scan of my lungs on 16Sep2021, and it shows there was covid-19) outcome was unknown.      DIAGNOSTIC RESULTS (normal ranges are provided in parenthesis if available): In March 2021, Heart rate: abnormal (abnormal) rapid pulse since March 2021. On 19-Jun-2021, Heart rate: irregular heart rate (abnormal) irregular heart rate. On 16-Sep-2021, Computerised tomogram: it shows there was covid-19 (abnormal) it shows there was covid-19. On 16-Sep-2021, Oxygen saturation: 96 to down 85 (Low) 96 to down 85. On an unknown date, Oxygen saturation: decreased (Low) Decreased.     For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments.   No Treatment information was provided.  The patient had the second shot in February, and since then, she had trouble with shortness of breath. She had rapid pulse since March 2021. She did an echo with the heart doctor and nothing showed up. However, on 19Jun2021, she did an EKG, and this showed that I have an irregular heart rate. On 21Jul2021, she ended up with congestive heart failure. She just got the results from the CAT scan of her lungs on 16Sep2021, and it shows there was covid-19. She never tested for covid, she never had a fever. The only thing that could have done this was the vaccine. Now, she can't do anything. If she does something, her oxygen falls down. She had been with oxygen ever since she had the heart failure.  She still needs the oxygen. She had fatigue, and her oxygen goes down, and her heart rate goes up. On 16Sep2021 was the first time she had dinner. Oxygen went from  96 to down 85. In the end, she couldn't get the dinner done.  On unknown date the patient experienced fatigue and decreased activity.  Company Comment: This case concerns a 80-year-old female patient with a previous relevant medical history of Sjogren's disease, Asthma and Pulmonary hypertension, who experienced the unexpected events of Heart rate irregular and Cardiac failure congestive after Spikevax (mRNA- 1273 vaccine / Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine). Additionally, Suspected COVID-19 was also reported. The onset of the event Heart rate irregular occurred approximately 4 months and 29 days after the second dose of Spikevax and Cardiac failure congestive 6 months after the second dose. COVID-19 was suspected because of an abnormal computerised tomogram performed 7 months and 26 days after the second dose, but the diagnosis was not confirmed. The rechallenge was not applicable, as the events were reported exclusively after the second dose. Previous history of pulmonary hypertension remains a confounder. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Parsonage-Turner Syndrome Following COVID-19 Vaccination; This is a literature report, 2021, DOI: 10.1148/radiol.2021211374, entitled Parsonage-Turner Syndrome Following COVID-19 Vaccination: MR Neurography.  Vaccination is one of the several known triggers of Parsonage-Turner syndrome (PTS). This report describes 2 individuals with clinical presentations of PTS whose symptoms began 13 hours and 18 days following receipt of the Pfizer-BioNTech BNT162b2 and Moderna mRNA-1273 COVID-19 vaccine, respectively. The diagnosis of PTS was confirmed using both electrodiagnostic testing and 3 Tesla magnetic resonance (MR) neurography. While research is needed to understand the association between PTS and COVID-19 vaccination, MR neurography may be used to confirm suspected cases of PTS as COVID-19 vaccines continue to be distributed worldwide. Parsonage-Turner syndrome (PTS; neuralgic amyotrophy) is a rare peripheral neuropathy typically characterized by sudden onset, severe upper arm pain followed by muscle weakness. Muscle weakness can be debilitating and up to two-thirds of patients experience long-term functional deficits. Materials and Methods: Two patients were referred for MR neurography between February and March 2021 due to clinically suspected PTS that developed 13 hours following the Pfizer-BioNTech (BNT162b2) COVID-19 vaccine and 18 days following the Moderna (mRNA-1273) COVID-19 vaccine. With informed consent from each participant, medical records were retrospectively reviewed for pertinent clinical and electrodiagnostic testing data as part of an ongoing, institutional review board- approved PTS registry compliant with the Health Insurance Portability & Accountability Act. A single musculoskeletal radiologist with greater than 7 years of MR neurography experience (DBS) reviewed 3-Tesla MR neurography and cervical spine MRI examinations. Results: Patient 1: A 49-year-old man was awoken by severe, electric shooting pain in his left volar forearm, 13 hours after receiving the first dose of the BNT162b2 vaccine (Pfizer-BioNTech) in his contralateral, right shoulder. Due to persistent, severe pain, he went to the emergency room where he received intravenous, non-steroidal anti-inflammatory medications, but these provided only mild relief. Laboratory tests performed in the emergency room, including C-reactive protein, erythrocyte sedimentation rate, complete blood count and comprehensive metabolic panels were all normal. His past medical history was significant for Lyme disease manifesting with an erythema migrains lessions, fatigue and myalgias 2 months prior and treated with doxycycline, although Lyme IgM and IgG antibodies also obtained in the emergency room were negative, The patient was discharged and treated with an oral, 8-days prednisone taper, at the end of which his pain subsided. Electrodiagnostic testing performed 9 days post onset was normal; specifically, no median nerve abnormality was identified on the nerve conduction or electromyography portions of the exam. The patient developed weakness in wrist flexion and forearm pronation the day after electromyography, along with numbness along a 1-inch strip in the middle, volar forearm region. Cervical spine and brachial plexus MRI performed 9 days post onset of initial pain symptoms did not demonstrate any findings to account for the patient's symptoms. Eight weeks post onset of initial pain, physical examination by a neurologist revealed mild atrophy in the left volar forearm and mild weakness in forearm pronation and wrist flexion (British Medical Research Council Scale strength 4+/5). MR neurography demonstrated prominent denervation edema pattern of the pronator teres (PT) and flexor carpi radials (FCR) muscles within the forearm. Within the arm, 4 severe hourglass-like constrictions and T2-weighted signal hyperintensity of the anteromedially positioned fascicular bundle of the median nerv0. Repeat e were detected; this bundle represents the PT/FCR bundle based on the known topographical, fascicular arrangement of the median nerve. Repeat electromyography, consistent with imaging findings, demonstrated severe denervation and no motor unit recruitment within the PT or FCR muscles. Muscles in the anterior interosseous nerve distribution were normal on MRI and electromyography. At 3 months' follow up post onset, the patient reported no residual pain but increased weakness. He had not yet received the second dose of his COVID-19 vaccine. Post-vaccination PTS typically ensure within 28 days of immunisation and has been reported as early as the same day as vaccination. Intrinsic, hourglass-like constrictions of affected nerves or nerve fascicles have been recognized in the acute phase of PTS10 and to date, they have not been observed in other spontaneous neuropathies. Patients 1 and 2 developed symptoms 13 hours and 18 days respectively, after receiving a COVID-19 vaccine, with MR neurography confirming the diagnosis by 8 and 5 weeks, respectively. While approximately half of all individuals with PTS report no identifiable trigger,1 the close temporal association between events suggests that vaccination may have been linked to PTS in these patients. Patient 1 received a clinical diagnosis of Lyme disease 2 months prior to PTS symptom onset despite negative OgM and IgG serologic tests, which have low sensitivity during early infection. He was treated with doxycycline and recovered prior to receiving the COVID-19 vaccine. In the report, 3 COVID-19 vaccines have received FDA Emergency Use Authorization. These include mRNA vaccines developed by Pfizer/BioNTech (BNT162b2) and Moderna (mRNA1273), as well as a one-dose, replication-incompetent human adenovirus vector vaccine developed by Johnson & Johnson/Janssen (Ad26.COV2.S). Additionally, some individuals will develop PTS within the post-vaccination window by chance alone. MR neurography is a useful diagnostic tool for PTS and may be particularly relevant as worldwide COVID-19 vaccinations increase. While there are currently no approved treatments, early, oral prednisone may reduce PTS symptom duration and severity. In recalcitrant cases, surgical neurolysis has also demonstrated efficacy. The timely and accurate diagnosis of PTS, which is often delayed, can help alleviate any undue stress for the patient and direct appropriate management. Patient 1. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. Caller is calling about the Pfizer COVID 19 vaccine. Something peculiar happened and she is not sure if it is related, and she knows they are still gathering a lot of data, so she wanted to report it and maybe help to tell if someone has experienced this she does not know if it is related but there is no other explanation. She is a healthy adult; she is strong and active. She is 70 years old. She got the vaccine 04 Mar and what happened to her was 6 days later which she knows is long for an adverse reaction, but she went to bed the night of the 6th day, all day that day she was fine, it was a normal day, she had no reaction to the vaccine up until that point other than just some tenderness where the injection was made but that's it. She went to bed that Wednesday night, it was 6 days after 04Mar, she woke up around 3 AM to go to the bathroom and she realized she was clammy, she had fever and chills on 11Mar2021, but the disturbing part was that she tried to stand up and got incredibly dizzy. She had to hold on to furniture to get the bathroom without falling. She said well she has a fever she better take an Aspirin, and this was really concerning, she tried to open the medicine cabinet and she couldn't seem to grab the bottle, she had like a loss of coordination, she tried to reach for the bottle and her hand couldn't quite get it. She had a hard time getting her hand to close around the bottle, she had trouble opening it. She had to try 3 times before she was able to hold on to one Aspirin. She made her way to the kitchen and had the same problem getting water in the glass. She could not grab things or coordinate anything, she finally got water and took the Aspirin and went to bed and she was so relieved to be back in bed. She woke up Thursday morning so that morning had been 1 full week since the vaccine. She felt perfectly fine that Thursday morning, it was like nothing had happened at all. patient received Daptacel instead of Adacel with no reported adverse event; 37 year old patient received Daptacel instead of Adacel with no adverse event; Initial information was received on 21-Sep-2021 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from other health care professional and consumer/non-healthcare professional via Medical information (under reference number - 00778953).  This case involves a 37-year-old female patient who was accidentally vaccinated with DIPHTHERIA-15/TETANUS/5 AC PERTUSSIS VACCINE [DAPTACEL] instead of the DIPHTHERIA, TETANUS AND ACELLULAR PERTUSSIS VACCINE [ADACEL] with no adverse event (Wrong product administered) (Product administered to patient of inappropriate age).  The patient's medical history, past medical treatment(s), concomitant therapy, vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  On 17-Sep-2021, the patient received a dose of suspect DIPHTHERIA-15/TETANUS/5 AC PERTUSSIS VACCINE [DAPTACEL] (lot number and expiry date not reported) via an unknown route at an unknown administration site for prophylactic vaccination (Wrong product administered) (Product administered to patient of inappropriate age).  It was reported "caller asks when can the Adacel be given? Also, when would the patient get an Adacel booster?."  There were no laboratory data/results available.  It was case of an actual medication error due to wrong vaccine administered and inappropriate age at vaccine administration (latency was on same day)  At the time of report, no adverse events were reported.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: have stayed in the bed all day; got my 1st one in August then went yesterday to get my second one, it; aching and hurts all over; fever; This case was reported by a consumer via interactive digital media and described the occurrence of generalized aching in a patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingles vaccine) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included chickenpox (had chickenpox when patient was kid). Concomitant products included SHINGLES VACCINE (NOS) (SHINGLES VACCINE).   On 19th September 2021, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingles vaccine. In September 2021, less than a week after receiving Shingles vaccine and an unknown time after receiving SHINGLES VACCINE, the patient experienced generalized aching and fever. On 19th September 2021, the patient experienced drug dose administration interval too short. On 20th September 2021, the patient experienced mobility decreased. On an unknown date, the outcome of the generalized aching and fever were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the mobility decreased and drug dose administration interval too short were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the generalized aching, fever and mobility decreased to be related to Shingles vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient self-reported this case. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient got the first shingle shot in august. The patient received second dose one month early, which led to shortening of vaccination schedule. The second shot did not hurt when patient got the vaccine but sometime during the night it started aching and hurts all over. The patient was running a fever and on the day of reporting patient stayed in the bed all day, hurting and running a fever. The patient would not ever get another one . The patient would better think twice before getting one.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Chickenpox (had chickenpox when patient was kid)

HCP was not sure were the subcutaneous area of the patient ended; HCP mentioned they've used a 5/8 needle on the patient instead of a 1 inch needle; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of intramuscular formulation administered by other route in a 54-year-old male patient who received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Fluarix Quadrivalent 2021-2022 season) (batch number 95K95, expiry date 30th June 2022) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included flu seasonal qiv dresden pre-filled syringe device (Fluarix Tetra Pre-Filled Syringe Device) injection syringe for prophylaxis.   On 20th September 2021, the patient received Fluarix Quadrivalent 2021-2022 season (subcutaneous) and Fluarix Tetra Pre-Filled Syringe Device. On 20th September 2021, unknown after receiving Fluarix Quadrivalent 2021-2022 season and Fluarix Tetra Pre-Filled Syringe Device, the patient experienced intramuscular formulation administered by other route and wrong technique in device usage process. On an unknown date, the outcome of the intramuscular formulation administered by other route and wrong technique in device usage process were unknown.   This report is made by GSK without prejudice and does not imply any admission or liability for the incident or its consequences.  Additional details were provided as follows: The nurse reported that the patient with a very substantial deltoid was administered Fluarix vaccine with a 5/8 needle on the patient instead of a 1 inch needle, which led to wrong technique in device usage process. Health care professional was not sure were the subcutaneous area of the patient ended, which led to intramuscular formulation administered by other route. No adverse effects were reported at the time of the reporting. The reporter consented to follow up either by email or phone. No further details were provided. Note: The event intramuscular formulation administered by other route was captured conservatively considering vaccine been administered subcutaneously.

GERD; hypertension; Hypothyroidism; Mayor depression disorder; Hyperparathyroidism secondary; Had pneumonia after the vaccine; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of PNEUMONIA (Had pneumonia after the vaccine), GASTROOESOPHAGEAL REFLUX DISEASE (GERD ), HYPERTENSION (hypertension ), HYPOTHYROIDISM (Hypothyroidism ), DEPRESSION (Mayor depression disorder ) and HYPERPARATHYROIDISM SECONDARY (Hyperparathyroidism secondary) in a female patient of an unknown age who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination.     No Medical History information was reported.    On an unknown date, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) 1 dosage form. On 02-Mar-2021, the patient experienced GASTROOESOPHAGEAL REFLUX DISEASE (GERD ) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), HYPERTENSION (hypertension ) (seriousness criterion hospitalization), HYPOTHYROIDISM (Hypothyroidism ) (seriousness criteria hospitalization and medically significant), DEPRESSION (Mayor depression disorder ) (seriousness criterion hospitalization) and HYPERPARATHYROIDISM SECONDARY (Hyperparathyroidism secondary) (seriousness criterion hospitalization). On an unknown date, the patient experienced PNEUMONIA (Had pneumonia after the vaccine) (seriousness criterion medically significant). At the time of the report, PNEUMONIA (Had pneumonia after the vaccine), GASTROOESOPHAGEAL REFLUX DISEASE (GERD ), HYPERTENSION (hypertension ), HYPOTHYROIDISM (Hypothyroidism ), DEPRESSION (Mayor depression disorder ) and HYPERPARATHYROIDISM SECONDARY (Hyperparathyroidism secondary) outcome was unknown.        The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Unknown) was unknown.       Concomitant medication use information was not provided by reporter. Treatment medication use information was not provided by reporter.  Company comment: This case concerns a female patient of an unknown age with no previous relevant medical history, who experienced the unexpected event of pneumonia. The events occurred on an unknown number of days after the first dose of mRNA-1273. The rechallenge was positive, as the events happened after the first dose and second dose have repeated. For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Unknown), the reporter considered MYOCARDITIS (Acute myocarditis), MALAISE (Malaise), COUGH (Dry cough), MYALGIA (Myalgias) and HEADACHE (Headache) to be possibly related.    Patient was in his usual state of health prior to getting the second dose of mRNA-1273 SARS-CoV-2 Vaccine. There was no family history of cardiovascular or autoimmune disease.  Endomyocardial biopsy was not performed as the patient experienced mild symptoms, had no haemodynamic or electrical instability, and responded promptly to initial management.  The patient was started on supportive therapy for the symptoms, including a brief course of intravenous diuretics for mild symptoms of congestion. Angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor and a beta-blocker therapy were commenced to treat systolic dysfunction. The patient was also initiated on colchicine to treat mild persistent chest pain, which was thought to be related to pericardial inflammation that resolved 4-5?days after presentation.   The patient was discharged home after 5 days of monitoring without evidence of electrical or haemodynamic instability and with Class I symptoms. One month later, repeat echocardiogram showed normalization of the left ventricular ejection fraction (56%) and size, no regional wall motion abnormalities, and normal longitudinal peak systolic strain. The patient remained asymptomatic and off diuretics.  This case concerns a 44-year-old male patient with a history of Obstructive sleep apnoea syndrome, Asthma and Obesity, who experienced the serious expected event Myocarditis. The event occurred approximately 4 days after the second and most recent dose of mRNA-1273 Moderna vaccine. The event was considered related to the study drug per the reporter's assessment. The event is consistent with the current understanding of the mechanism of action of the study medication. The benefit-risk relationship of mRNA-1273 Moderna vaccine is not affected by this report. Since that time she has been experiencing generalized weakness, poor appetite, and fevers. More recently she has developed shortness of breath which has been progressing as well as cough. She was treated with Decadron 6 mg daily for 4 days.  Which she will continue for 6 more days.  She was not a candidate for remdesivir, due to she was symptomatic >10 days.  She should stay in isolation until she finish her Decadron. Initially she required oxygen support, but by the time of discharge she was in her home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 4/17/21, I had the first dose (Lot EW0164).  Here is a summary of my symptoms following the first dose: ~3 hrs after the vaccine, I had numbness and tingling on left side of my face, including the left side of my tongue (followed by 1st trip to ER). The next day, I had unilateral numbness on the entire left side of my body from the top of my head to the bottom of my foot (followed by 2nd trip to ER that included a CT scan and MRI). The numbness lasted about 3 days, turned to tingling (similar to when your leg ?falls asleep? and starts to ?wake up?), and then pain before the symptoms mostly subsided. A few hours later (this is now 4/20), I had a migraine (I get headaches often, but this was the 3rd migraine that I?ve had in my life ? ibuprofen/Tylenol rotation did not help and only when I was able to finally sleep was there some relief). Following the migraine, the unilateral numbness returned (4/21). A neurologist started me on a 5-day Prednisone treatment; symptoms mostly subsided, but the unilateral numbness returned on the 3rd day of the treatment (4/23). Over the first two weeks following the shot, I logged my daily symptoms as they occurred. In addition to the numbness and the migraine, my log included at various times: other headaches, pressure behind eyes, pressure in one ear, pounding heart (yet normal heart rate), pain in left chest, cramps (legs, feet, side ? noted well hydration), short/sharp pain in side, forgetfulness, body aches, pressure in chest with deep breaths, tired, etc. Weeks 3-4 after the shot, I noted a rash on left leg.   Yesterday, I received my second shot. The symptoms seem to be coming on a quicker timeline. ~75 min after the shot numbess in left face (I was sure to get the shot on the right arm this time, first shot was in  the left arm with left side numbness...this one right arm shot , but still left side numbness). Quickly spread to numbness on full left side of the body. The numbness was present when I woke up this morning and turned to tingling (similar to when your leg ?falls asleep? and starts to ?wake up?) and now pain. I've also noted on my log: forgetfulness (my wife called me loopy), pressure behind left eye, pressure in left ear, pain in right chest (where my heart would be but other side - rather brief)... if I'm on the same path as the first shot with just a faster timeline, the migraine is up next. Plus I've had a few blood tests: 1 was ordered by the neurologist (4/20/21 - no concerns on his end he only noted slightly elevated vitamin D) and another blood test order by primary dr near end of July 2021 to check if i had indicators for Gilbert's syndrome (which my dad has but my blood test results and past blood test results indicate that I don't have it).
PRIOR_VAX: Pfizer covid vaccine 1st dose on 4/17/21

The next day I woke up in cold sweats. I still had the ongoing fatigue, ears were hurting, sore throat, body aches. This lasted for 2 days. Friday was the first day I woke up without cold sweats. Currently, my ears feel very tender/sensitive. It feels as if my ear was scraped out and left raw. My throat feels similar to when I got my tonsils out. The biggest thing I have is anxiety. The intensity will vary but the sensation is still there. I feel butterflies in my throat. Like a fight or flight sensation takes over. My mind is not anxious, but my body is. For example, if I am driving and come across a red light, I get overwhelmed which is very unusual for me. I am not an anxious person. Getting gowned up for work was not something that would ever make me anxious, and it does now. I was prescribed Vistaril which is not doing anything. My blood pressure was 132/84 also which is high for me. I thought it might play a role in the anxious feeling. I was told to take Prilosec because the butterflies feeling in my throat could've been reflux due to the location of the sensation but that is not working. I also still have ongoing fatigue, I am always tired and have no energy. Fatigue and anxiety are the most prominent and concerning symptoms. My doctor thought that maybe because my metabolism is slow, my body is taking longer to metabolize the vaccine. I don't know that this is permanent but has been going on since around the date of vaccine.

August 3rd 2021, 6 weeks after the COVID-19 vaccination administration, the patient (myself) started to experience symptoms of a blocked tear duct that evolved into dacryocystitis, which was resistant to PO and IV antibiotics and continued to worsen despite an I & D. At which time, September 11th 2021, an MRI was done which showed a mass near the lacrimal sac. Biopsy results showed necrotic Granulomas with numerous acid fast bacilli consistent with a mycobacterial infection. Currently speciation and sensitivities are unknown. Modified RIPE therapy had been implemented with the concern that IV antibiotics may also need to be used depending on PCR and culture results.  I have yet to recover from this infection and have been out of work since 8/13. I have lost weight, suffer from right sided headaches, right eye pain, slightly blurred vision on the right side, and will have a facial deformity due to the I&D and surgery. I also suffer from fatigue and general malaise.  I will still require at least one more surgery to reconstruct the lacrimal duct system.  While I understand that one could argue that I am immunocompromised due to the medications I?m on for Crohn?s disease, I would argue that I do not have a history of infections, risky personal habits or travel. I am vegan, plant based and work out daily. With mycobacterial infections commonly known as opportunistic, I have to wonder if the vaccine altered my immune response, allowing for the mycobacterium to proliferate and cause a serious infection.
LAB_DATA: Routine lab work has been WNL except for a slightly low WBC of 3.0 on September 22, 2021. September 11th, MRI done which showed mass near lacrimal sac measuring 2.0 x 1.5 x 3.7 cm.  Biopsy performed on September 14, 2021 with roughly 1cm x 1cm specimen sent to pathology was negative for malignancy but showed necrotic Granulomas and numerous acid fast bacilli.  Specimen was sent to lab around September 13, 2021 for PCR testing to get speciation of the mycobacterium. The results are not back. Multiple cultures have been taken within the past couple weeks and have been negative for growth thus far.

Pt provides some information, majority of info provided by significant other that is at the bedside.    Pt was diagnosed with 8/31 with COVID 19 in the emergency department. He presented back to the ED on 9/13 with increased dyspnea, increased fatigue, decreased oxygen saturation, and fever. Pt was then admitted to the pulmonary floor to the hospitalist services.    He remained on the pulmonary floor. He did require more supplemental oxygen and was eventually receiving maximum amounts of oxygen via heated high flow NC with a nonrebreather on top. He was also started on IV dexamethasone on admission. Decision was made to transfer the patient to the ICU for AVAPS.    Pt arrived to the ICU. He was placed on NIV. He did become anxious with application, so he was started on precedex. Pt is alert and oriented. His fiance is at bedside.    Hospital Course:  Patient was transferred to the ICU on 9/19/2021 due to worsening respiratory status and was transition to noninvasive ventilatory support.  He required a dexmedetomidine infusion for anxiety.  He further decompensated on 9/23/2021 and required intubation.  He suffered a spontaneous left pneumothorax and a chest tube was placed.  He required paralytic infusion as well.  He was initiated on broad-spectrum antibiotics while in the ICU for a possible secondary bacterial infection.  Unfortunately, the patient continued to decompensate despite maximal mechanical support.  On the evening of 9/26/2021, the patient's family mid determination to transition to comfort measures and terminal extubation. On September 1, 2021 at 12:25 p.m. I received the Pfizer-BioNtech COVID-19 vaccine from employee. The vaccine as injected into my left arm intermuscular into my deltoid muscle. The next day I had constant metal taste in my mouth, and which has not changed to this day along with weakness. A few days later I started having palpitations and feeling very light headed and short of breath. Along with severe headaches this issue has continued to increase. On September 9th 2021 while at work, I attempted to get up from my chair and felt extremely dizzy and started to fall at that point a co-worker grabbed me and helped me back into my chair and proceeded to get my blood pressure which was very elevated for my baseline. My coworkers at that point called one of the nurses that I work with to come and evaluate me and my blood pressure remained elevated then one of the doctors that I work with came in to do an assessment on me she listened to my heart and my lungs, at that time she advised for me to have an EKG.    Once all of my symptoms continued to worsen, I called my doctor to have an appointment due to all the health issues that I have experience since the vaccine. They took my vitals and preformed an EKG which showed to be abnormal. I have been referred to cardiology now due to the health complications since the vaccine. The following day while at work the symptoms were increasing with my blood pressure and tachycardia, When I returned from my lunch break, I felt very weak and lightheaded. When I reach my floor to my department my nurse manager was there and saw that I was not feeling well. She then took my blood pressure and it was so elevated that they called a code blue on me. I was transported via ambulance to Hospital and they performed 2 EKGs on me there. After being in the back of the ER they moved me to the lobby due to all the exam room being torn up from the new construction that they are doing. At the time of the vaccination, no adverse affects. I got the first dose in my left arm (due to being at a drive-thru site). Barely any soreness at all (discomfort 1/10). I sleep on that side, so I asked for dose #2 in my right arm. It was exactly three weeks later. No side effects, no fever, no nausea, hardly felt it at the injection site. Not much discomfort (scale 3/10 in my arm).  After almost 2-3 weeks, started to see a rash, which got more extensive and was later diagnosed via biopsy as being: Granuloma annulare. The rash started on my upper arms, near the vaccine site and has spread quite a bit.  SEE CONTINUATION PAGE for a full history of this issue and what has been tried to date..... The rash started on my upper arms, near the vaccine site and now covers both arms, is also on both legs, my chest and neck.   __The rash started about 2-3 weeks after my second dose of Pfizer. I thought it was stress, as I was retiring on 5/8, in just another 2 weeks.... This assumption that it was stress caused me to delay seeing my doctor (my mother used to break out in hives from stress, regularly). At that time, it was mostly on my upper arms - heavily on the outer side and some spots on the inner side, and starting on the backs of my calves with a few spots on the front of my thighs. __I finally saw my doctor on 5/17 when I was clear that it needed to be seen. Doctor thought it was a histamine reaction to something. But I had not changed ANYTHING in my diet, no new/different soaps, no new clothes, no new sheets, we could not identify anything different that could have caused an allergic reaction. Doctor started me on OTC at first: benadryl cream and claritin 1x/day, with instructions to come back in two weeks. This regimen did not help and the rash got worse. __Second office visit with Doctor  on 6/3:  we tried a different regimen, adding a prescription ointment: Triamcinolone Acetonide Topical, and  upping the OTC antihistamines. Claritin in AM and Zyrtec in PM. (since they had different ingredients). Still didn't clear it up at all. Instead, it was spreading down my arms and more on my legs. __Office visit #3 to Doctor  on 6/14: Since treating it like a histamine reaction was not having any effect, he took a biopsy so we could definitely know what it was. Got the results 6/22. Doctor  prescribed a steroid cream, with instructions 2 weeks on/2 weeks off. I used this for two weeks, results were not great..... I then found a medical dermatologist who was familiar with my diagnosis.  __7/13: Met with Physician Assistant at Dermatologist.  He was very familiar with Granuloma annulare. We went with a cream and a steroid pill:  Prednisone - 20 mg/day for 10 days then reduce to 10 mg/day for 10 days. And Pimecrolimus Cream 1% (generic for Elidel Cream 1%). Instructed to apply cream 2x/day. Ran out pretty quickly, as the rash was extensive on my arms and legs.  __8/3: Visit #2 with Physician Assistant. Rash seemed better. Was less red and smoother to the touch. Renewed prescription for Prednisone (waited until 8/16 to take the next round, due to a trip and wanting to put some time between steroid treatments).  Used the cream at least once daily, sometimes twice. Found it difficult to plan when to apply it, due to wanting to avoid being "slimy" around other people or sitting on furniture or handling my contact lenses.  __My own assessment is that the Prednisone does not make a big difference for the rash. But the cream does - though only if I apply it heavily and frequently. If I miss a few applications, then the rash gets visibly worse, and quickly. The rash is now also on my upper chest and I can feel the bumpiness on sides and back of my neck. It is much worse on my lower arms - both outside and inside, as well as the inside of my upper arms. It has also spread on my legs. The back of my calves are much worse, it is now behind my knees and starting up the back of my thigh. And on the front of the thighs it has spread upwards and to the inside. Also, on my left foot, there was one small spot in the middle of my arch (on the top of the foot). That spot is now larger and there is a second spot closer to my ankle.  __I will make another appointment with the Dermatologist. I am despondent at how bad I look, that I cannot get massages and cannot spend much time outside to go hiking (the cream says to avoid contact with eyes and avoid direct sunlight). "Medical search" says that Granuloma annulare will clear up on its own but may take a couple YEARS to clear up. I don't know how I can hang in there that long. We are retired and both fully vaccinated and wanting to start traveling. But I can't....looking like this.   I have never had any reaction to a vaccination, ever, other than the normal expected discomfort as the vaccine does its job creating antibodies. I had my Shingles vaccine (#1 10/15/19 and #2 on 3/11/20), more than a year before this vaccine. And I get my flu shot every year, last one was 10/16/20.
LAB_DATA: Biopsy, samples taken 6/4/21, processed by Lab. Diagnosis: Granuloma annulare.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediately the next day, after the 2nd vaccine, I had flu like symptoms for probably a little more than 24 hours. I was exhausted and slept. And I really tired for several days after. Within about 30 days, my right pinkie at the tip had a little bit of minor numbness and then it began to spread into the entire pinky and into the ring finger and then into the wrist, elbow and sometimes into the shoulder. I spoke to an Orthopedist after it was really getting real pronounced.  I was evaluated and he thought it was Ulna Neuropathy. He wanted me to evaluated by Neurology first to make sure it was that. So the doctor evaluated me with the right upper extremity nerve conduction and it was abnormal and then she did EMGs on both upper extremities and two weeks later repeated them and did both upper and lower extremities an due to loss -  CIDP - Chronic Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyneuropathy. It is very similar to Guiliann Barrett but this is a chronic and incurable version of Gillian Barrett. She Regulatory Authority - it is an Acronym - Multi-focal neuropathy. I have begun IVIG - IV immuno-globulin therapy - I have had  10 of those treatments. Typically after two or three treatments of this you get dramatically better from CIDP but I have neuropathy in the feet and I have to walk with a cane now. I"m literally getting worse every day. And I'm having PT and OT therapy and am scheduled for a speech evaluation. I can't use my right dominant hand - t he first three fingers at all. OT eval was yesterday - 30 day evaluation  - and I have dramatically lost significant strength between thumb and index fingers which are the only two fingers in my right hand that have use but I have a 10th of a grip that I have on my left side (which is non dominant side). I can't stand unassisted for 10 minutes. I have speech things (issues) come in when I start getting tired - inflammatory process in the brain and it's called Bulbar Neuropathy - Cerebral nerve 9-12 - get pinched off signals. The neurologist said she's seen 4 or 5 cases who have had things that flare up after the second COVID shot. Like people have had things that are slow simmering - there seems to be a correlation to those people who have had a flare after the second shot. And the treatment now is going to include some IV or Oral steroids - but it's not certain which. Then there are some chemicals and maybe chemotherapy which work with this to suppress the immune system. The numbness is starting to come in the left pinkie as well of my left hand. I have that  pinkie, ring finger and my middle finger splinted because I have cannot move them on my own. I can still make the pinkie finger move although slowly.  I can't use my dominant hand anymore and I can't walk unassisted and it is likely permanent.
LAB_DATA: Neurologist - has ordered all the tests and bloodwork. After the first visit, I had 20 something vials taken at Hospital.  ER visit - there was one of those visits - around the time of my first round of treatments - my immunity was low and I got a stomach bug and ended up in ER. They gave me IVs and Anti-imetics (to stop me from vomiting) and some Motrin.

No head trauma although she did fall and twisted her ankle right before this began. No other sxs.  PLAN: No orders of the defined types were placed in this encounter. - Smell/taste disorder- in the absence of allergy/sinus issues and trauma- likely idiopathic. May be age related. SYMPTOM_TEXT: On June 13, 2021 I was admitted to Emergency Room for severe abdominal pain and vomiting.  This was 2 days prior to me starting my menstrual cycle.  While the ER doctor could find nothing specific wrong, I proceeded to be in significant pain for the next 3 days, and then exhausted for the 3 days after that.  I bled heavily and lost 11 lbs.  Although I had experienced somewhat heavy periods prior to my COVID-19 vaccination, I had never experienced such extreme pain.  I continue, even now, to have severe abdominal pain prior to my menstrual cycle, during my menstrual cycle, and during ovulation.  Sometimes the pain is so severe I vomit.  I am no longer losing a significant amount of weight but I also have less of an appetite because of these painful episodes.  I am having to take prescription strength pain medication to be able to live my life during the time prior to my menstrual cycle, during my menstrual cycle, and during ovulation.  I've had two ultrasounds, a colonoscopy, an endoscopy, a pap smear, and blood drawn.  Nothing is showing up as being wrong.  Last week I had an IUD placed as an attempt to ease this pain.  I have no idea if this is associated with the COVID-19 vaccine but it is worth looking into because my life is still not back to normal and the only difference was getting that vaccine two months prior to the pain starting.
LAB_DATA: two ultrasounds (one on my abdomen and one vaginal ultrasound), a colonoscopy, an endoscopy, a pap smear, and blood drawn. Nothing note-worthy found on any of these tests.  All looked fine.
OTHER_MEDS: Lexapro 20mg; Wellbutrin 300mg; Adderall 10mg; Ambien 10mg; Probiotic; Zyrtec

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I started with a yeast infection and they gave me terconazole. By Thursday night 08/12/2021  I had what I thought was mosquito bites. It went from my neck and I had some on forehead which was on L side which I thought was from Nickel because I get acne from too much Nickel.  On Sunday 08/15/2021 after medication,  I had a  (about size of an apple) rash with lines that showed up on left buttocks and I said it was a reaction to medication. I went to Dr on Monday and they didn?t know what it was. I went to dermatology on Tuesday and she said I had poison ivy which I didn't believe because I don?t go outside in nature. I was itchy and they gave trimenazone cream but that made it worse. Over the next 48 hours I had hives on left side of stomach and hip and under left breast that was likethe size of a  covid arm circle that was big as an orange if you lifted up left breast. I had a very small circle on right side but that was only thing on right side. Friday I had cortisone shot. That weekend I was miserable with itching and Monday I went back for blood work to make sure I didn?t have Lyme disease and that turned up negative and  so I had a biopsy and they said it was allergic reaction to something. I couldn?t get into my allergist but she referred me to another allergist and as soon as he started listening to my story he linked it back to vaccine to the PEG and Propylene in the vaccine and he said my body got overloaded with that medication and that was why I had reaction, and as we speak now I have had patch testing, I have 90 squares of chemicals on and they come off tomorrow and Friday we will do a reading to see if we had contact with any allergy on back. I was also tired, had chills, 36 hours with chills without fever, 4 hours of nausea, headache, being tired. Had vaccine on a Thursday and Saturday I was up and fine. My biggest reaction was on left butt cheek. I took that medication 2 years ago and didn?t have reaction. It took 3 weeks to recover

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received Moderna #2 vaccine after getting Pfizer #1 the previous month, and experienced negative side effects in the 15 minute monitoring period. Details as follows:  - Patient booked and appointment for Moderna Vaccine #2 with no record of previous #1 vaccine. Upon arrival, we asked to produce their vaccination card, but they did not have it. As such, prior to administering, we verified clinical background and confirmed with them that they were getting the Moderna #2, which they confirmed yes.  - After administration, during the 15 minute monitoring period, patient reported having increased heartrate, chest discomfort, and nausea. Stated having history of similar reactions to vaccines/injections and anxiety increasing during these. - Patient was asked to wait 15 more minutes.  - After 15 more minutes, patient symptoms had not completely subsided. As a result, we informed the patient they should not drive/leave alone, should have someone with them, and that they should see a medical provider immediately if their symptoms did not subside/worsen.  - Afterwards, patient stated that they had actually gotten Pfizer vaccine in the previous month. Explained to them that the difference vaccine is the reason why they reacted more negatively to a difference vaccine. Re-emphasized that patient should not leave alone and to see a medical provider ASAP if symptoms did not go away/worsened. - Patient confirmed they had somebody to drive/monitor them and left after acknowleding that they should go to ED if symptoms remain.
PRIOR_VAX: Increased heart rate, anxiety after vaccine

On September 18, I woke up at 7am and found my left arm was extremely cold (like ice cold), my left arm was numb, I realized I had been sweating while asleep and I felt "off" - the most strangest "off" feeling I've ever felt.  I called 911 and at my request, I was transported to the emergency room.  Initial blood work showed my troponin levels were 1.2.  I was admitted and the following three blood tests showed my troponin levels as follows:  3.2 at 2pm on Sept. 18, 1.8 at 8pm on Sept. 18 and 1.0 at 2am on Sept. 19.  I remained in the hospital until the afternoon of Sept. 20.  Please see item 19 for additional information.
LAB_DATA: While hospitalized, numerous diagnostic tests were conducted to include CT scans, MRI's, echocardiogram as well as heart catheterization.  The heart catheterization revealed no blockages in my heart.  The echocardiogram revealed the wall thickness of my heart was slightly increased and the left ventricle was mildly dilated.  All the diagnostic testing did not identify any plausible cause for the increase in my troponin levels.  ***Doctor told me today (Sept 28, 2021) that what I experienced was probably caused by the COVID vaccine.***
HISTORY: Back condition, plantar fasciitis, tinnitus, gastritis

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client ambulated on her own to clinic check-in and stated that she wanted her vaccine but was also anxious about receiving it. During the pre-screening she stated she had history of anaphylaxis to the following: cinnamon, lilacs, lilies and colognes but no other substances. She filled out the rest of her paperwork without assistance; there were no documented reasons to refuse vaccine administration. She ambulated normally to vaccination station and received vaccine without complications and then ambulates self to observation area for normal 15 minute observation period. After normal 15 minute observation period was over she was noticed by clinic staff to not look well: she was pale and looked "sick". Clinic staff questioned her about how she felt and stated that she, "felt woozy". Staff brought cot to her side and she sat down and stated she felt like her throat was closing so staff immediately called emergency number for EMS assistance. Client started to list to her left side and staff aided her in laying down, she did not lose consciousness. Staff retrieved cool packs for her and helped her to remain still until EMS arrived. Prior to EMS arrival staff see red blotchy patches appear on her neck and chest and she again stated that she felt "foggy". Epinephrine was prepared for administration but was never given.  Fire EMS arrives at 1747 hrs who assess until ambulance arrives shortly later. No difficulty breathing was found and she developed no signs of wheezing or rales. She is overheard by clinic staff to admit to Fire personnel that she has anaphylaxis to penicillin, this is not declared on her written paperwork or to clinic staff at time of check-in.   V/S: 1738 hrs  BP 159/62  P 110 bounding 1740 hrs BP 155/81  P 118 bounding

I believe the surgeon told me the two spots on the left nostril, did not appear connected.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Alongside headache and fatigue, I experienced notably increased heart rate. I have chronic tachycardia, likely [non-covid-related] POTS (and several medications that worsen this as a side effect), but I take Metoprolol to treat this. As a result, I typically have an HR of 80-95 when sitting at rest. On the 16th, it was 120-140+ when sitting/laying at rest. After my first appointment of the day, I had to drop the rest of my plans to rest, and I slept about 16 hours. This also happened after the second dose, but I was unsure if it was related to the vaccine, as I had made several errors with my daily medications that week and had gotten little sleep. This was not the case after third dose, yet the symptoms were worse. After 16 hours of sleep, the symptoms largely subsided, and if boosters were to be offered annually going forward, I would continue to take them despite these symptoms, but the effect on my HR was arguably substantive, so I figured I should report. *I also had soreness at the injection site, which was mild and expected. I also had swelling of my lymph nodes on the left side only, at the base of my neck. I've never had this reaction to a vaccine before, including previous doses of this vaccine (all Moderna), and I've never had swelling this extreme from an active infection either.

The patient responded well to intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG), hydrocortisone and methylprednisolone therapy.

On Saturday the 18th I woke up with a sore throat and a headache.  Sunday, I has a worse sore throat and headache.  Monday, I still didnt feel well.  Tuesday I felt just fine.  On Wednesday, sept 22, I woke around 4 a.m. thinking my leg was asleep.  I moved around and realised it wasnt going away.  My left calf, the sensation is not "normal".  Almost like how it feels when your foot is waking up from "falling asleep".  Today is 9/28/21, I have been to the walk in clinic and ER.  Both referred me to Neurology but all the neurologists around cant see me or wont, I'm not sure.   I have been diagnosed with Arnold chiari Malformation.  I have not had any Chiari symptoms for 2.5 yrs.  Since getting Moderna, I have had a headache and my left calf feels "numb/asleep" ever since!
