SYMPTOM_TEXT: hives throughout body and itching

About five minutes after getting my shot my arm felt cold my fingertips kind of Tangled stuff that I was expecting. And then my lips started tingling, they didn't plump up like they do when I eat something I'm allergic to. They did get a little chubby but I have no idea how much I was wearing my mask and I didn't necessarily have a mirror. That and I didn't feel like they got super big. I realize they must have got a little bigger than I thought the next day because when I could feel them it kind of felt like it I don't know really how to describe that unless you've had an allergic reaction you don't know what I'm talkin about or if you ever got your swollen before. But my face ended up going numb that was more concerning. I was offered a Benadryl and a water. I did not accept I was told I didn't need to go to the doctors or I needed to go to the doctors only if I was having trouble breathing or rash appeared. None of that stuff happened. I waited for an hour I wasn't really checked on I have people stopped and talked to me but it wasn't so much to check on me it was curiosity as to what happened because they were standing around when I told him that I was having a bad reaction. I also had a get some kind of cold sweat when I first talked to him but that went away rather quickly. My vision did go wonky a couple of times but as I sat there it kind of chilled out. That was basically it I was advised by somebody else at the Pharmacy I don't know who they are to contact my doctor the next day if I did not go in. Today my face has been partially numb and spots on and off and at times very itchy. Since I'm used to allergies and I have an EpiPen available I did not need to go into the hospital which was already overcrowded. If my face stayed numb and wasn't getting better I had planned to go in. I have had weird effects like what I have mentioned on and off today my lips feel weird sometimes my face feels itchy and sometimes numb in spots. This is not normal for me in any way shape or form. As for everything else there's no hives there's no anything at the injection site there's no bruising it's a little warm and feels like it's bruised but not a bad bruise. I did talk to my doctor they do not advise me to get the second dose. They also advised me to talk to an allergist to write a medical exemption form as they are concerned with what could happen the next time I get to shot considering the Doctors told me that the second shot could have worst side effects. I was told this before the shot. As the packet he gave me was all about moderna I was told who I talk to and that is not normally what they're back sheet looks like it was a couple pages but everything was about moderna and I was under the impression that I was going to be contacted the day that I was in there however when I asked him if we could go ahead you the paperwork so I could leave he handed me the packet I just mentioned opened up to the page where I should contact you and told me all the information I needed was in that packet and then proceeded off to go do something behind the Pharmacy Counter. I didn't look at the paperwork until today because I wasn't feeling well. Also he reassured me that I got the Pfizer shot because that's the only saw that they carry at that particular . He also said he was going to check out next time they printed out the papers to make sure that it was printing out the packet how it was supposed to. I would also like to note that I was not really asked what was wrong with me I had to volunteer that information myself they didn't really seem to care what my symptoms were. It felt like I was in a less they know conversation. Had I had felt better or I was thinking straight I probably would have gone into the hospital. To me I was just trying to stay calm and I think I made myself feel less panicked then I should have been. I was trying not to cry or freak out as there were other patients and I knew I had to make sure my kids were picked up first. But even after they were picked up I still felt scared. It's like they did not care I felt like a side show where everybody was like what's happening and then once they knew they didn't care they just walked off. I tried to keep my mind off it I talked to a couple people in there try to keep my nerves level. I know this last part of the helpful but I just think the whole thing was handled not so well. I'm not a hysterical person but that's how I felt inside. Sorry the grammar and punctuation are very good I am doing this on my phone it has its own autocorrect craziness happening.
LAB_DATA: Nothing was done as I was basically advised not to go in unless I couldn't breathe or develops hives or was in a worse condition than what was going on.
HISTORY: I have bad reactions to most any type of birth control.

Starting 5 min after injection, my chest started hurting. Figured it must be anxiety and breathed through, but it didn?t change. The next several nights it was intense enough to keep me awake, HR only slightly elevated (5-10 beats) and oxygen 96-98% instead of my normal 98-100%. Mostly constant with further pressure/pain in the chest with activity. Short of breath with exertion. Very fatigued. No headache, no body ache, no nausea, minimal arm pain. Started ibuprofen and after several days of that, it was more intermittent. It feels like a raw pressure in the chest. It seems like it is improving but was still very present today without ibuprofen. It feels similar to the deep sensation from when I had radiation for hodgkins in 2012. My doctor and I feel it is likely radiation recall syndrome.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Vaccine 1 given 2/5/21. On 2/24/21 was running a fever and not feeling well. On 2/25/21 - I went to the doctor. See attached office visit forms.

A few days after the shot, I had some pain in my left leg (calf), and noticed a lump about 1" or so in size, with internal swelling in an area of about 2 to 3".  This was strange because I have never had something like this before, and I have not played sports or had any real opportunity to hurt my leg physically, nor have I engaged in any activity that could have physically impacted the area. I noticed this a few days after the shot, but I suspect it started earlier and I had not noticed until a few days later when it hurt. I have monitored the site and it reached its peak about one week after the vaccine and then stayed that way for a few days, then gradually subsided. I still have the lump, but it is much reduced and does not hurt any more. I hesitated to take the second dose appointment worried that it could be related to the vaccine dose, and if it is, I am worried if this kind of swelling (or maybe it is an internal clot) or whatever it was, could turn up in  a more vital area of my body, such as my brain, where it could be dangerous.
LAB_DATA: I asked the pharmacy where I took the shot and they said I should have it checked out at the ER! This was not an emergency, and my insurance has a deductible, and I would have to take time off work at a very busy time at work so I could not chase this. Further, knowing this is not a real ER emergency I know I would be lowest priority and wait in line all day, then I cannot imagine the ER would be able to diagnose on the spot something like this without specialized tests at  a different clinic, which means I would be bouncing around from clinic to clinic, wasting both a lot of time, and a lot of money, and I am very skeptical I would get a reliable diagnosis even in some clinic, since, if this was indeed covid related, I suspect no clinic has experience with symptoms from a brand new cause, and they would most likely try to classify it as something else.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving my first shot of the Moderna vaccine, immediately I noticed that my legs felt very heavy. The same night, my calves were extremely sore and my left calf continued to be sore for days after getting the shot. Along with being sore, I felt this pulsating feeling in my calf that was constant throughout the day. This went on for about 10 days until the pulsating feeling traveled to my left thigh. It was very clear that the pulsating feeling was actually my muscle twitching. I could see my thigh muscle twitching very clearly through my skin. This twitching occurred all day, every day until the time of my 2nd shot. Three days after receiving the 2nd dose of the vaccine which I received on September 1st, 2021, the muscle twitching began again but in every muscle in my body this time. The twitching is sporadic and occurs in different muscle groups including my thighs, calves, buttocks, intercostal muscles, back, shoulders, forearm, triceps, chest, hamstrings, eyes, tongue and lips. The muscle twitching occurs at rest, while standing and while sitting. Some days the twitching is more intense and I can see I through my skin, other days they are less intense where I can feel them, however, they are not visible through my skin. There has not been a day where I have not experienced these fasiculations since receiving my first dose of the moderna vaccination.  It has been almost a total of two months of experiencing muscle twitching. I have seen my primary doctor, a neurologist and been to an Emergency room. I believe it is possible that the vaccine triggered a central nervous system response that is causing neuron excitability. My primary care doctor prescribed Diazepam 5mg to aid with the twitches, primarily at night so I am able to sleep, however, I can still feel the twitches mildly even after taking the medication. Certain locations such as my left thigh, and right upper back  seem to be popular locations for the muscle twitches. The twitches often occur the longest and the most often in those muscles. Lastly, sometimes, a dull ache/soreness accompanies the twitching. Usually in my entire arm or legs.

This literature marketed report has been received from the authors of a published literature article, titled as stated above, containing retrospectively measured using 2 matched cohorts and refers to 39 patients of unknown gender with median age 74.3 (61.3-95.6) years without a history of immunosuppression who were seen by their primary care provider at some point in the years 2000 through 2015. There was no information about the patients' concurrent conditions, concomitant therapies, drug reactions, allergies or medical history provided. The patients did not have history of HIV/AIDS, leukemia, lymphoma, myeloma, myelodysplastic syndrome and did not have history of any prescription of the immunomodulating druganti-IL6, B-cell blockade, calcineurin inhibitors, costimulation blockade, disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs, interleukin-1 inhibitors, interleukin-17 inhibitors, monoclonal TNF-alpha antibody, mammalian target of rapamycin (mTOR) inhibitors, tumor necrosis factor (TNF) inhibitors, chemotherapy, and 2 or more prescriptions of glucocorticoids within the past year.  On unknown dates, the patients were vaccinated with live attenuated herpes zoster vaccine (manufacturer unknown) (formulation, strength, dose, route of administration, lot # and expiration date were not reported) for prophylaxis.  On unknown dates, the patients developed giant cell arteritis (GCA). 16 patients (41%) were diagnosed via positive biopsy and 23 (59%) were diagnosed by nonpathological College of Rheumatology clinical criteria. The median time from live attenuated herpes zoster (ZVL) vaccination to a diagnosis of GCA was a median (range) of 37.7 (4.9�104.3) months, with peaks around 15 months and 45 months The outcome of the event was unknown.  According to authors, matched comparison of ZVL vs non-ZVL patients showed that vaccinated patients had a significantly higher incidence of GCA. This association may potentially be attributed to (1) subacute or persistent arterial wall infection with ZVL, (2) a ZVL vaccine-driven cellular immune response to VZV already present in the arterial walls, or (3) a non-viralspecific autoimmune reaction triggered by ZVL. Using proportional hazards regression models of time to GCA by combination of both diagnostic case criteria, ZVL vaccination was associated with an increased risk of GCA diagnosis (hazard ratio [HR], 2.20; 95% CI, 1.50�3.24; P < .0001). In the more specific, biopsy-confirmed subset of GCA cases, ZVL receipt remained a significant risk factor for GCA (HR, 2.70; 95% CI, 1.48�4.95; P = .004). The authors performed a secondary analysis incorporating only those patients from the original matched cohort whose follow-up period included the year 2008 (the first year of widespread ZVL availability and use) or any subsequent years. In this subset (n = 62 395 patients with 130 GCA diagnoses), ZVL vaccination remained a significant risk factor for GCA diagnosis via all diagnostic criteria (HR, 2.35; 95% CI, 1.58�3.47; P < .0001) and for GCA diagnosis by positive biopsy alone (57 GCA diagnoses; HR, 2.91; 95% CI, 1.57�5.38; P = .0007).  A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.  This is non valid report due to lack of patients' identifiers.
